      <TOCHeading>Record Description</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Summary Information</Description>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>1</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <Description>Physical Description</Description>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/CARBON%20DIOXIDE&quot;&gt;CARBON DIOXIDE&lt;/a&gt; is a colorless odorless gas at atmospheric temperatures and pressures. Relatively nontoxic and noncombustible. Heavier than air and may asphyxiate by the displacement of air. Soluble in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. Forms &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt;, a mild acid. Under prolonged exposure to heat or fire the container may rupture violently and rocket. Used to freeze food, to control chemical reactions, and as a fire extinguishing agent.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>2</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <Description>Physical Description</Description>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/CARBON%20DIOXIDE&quot;&gt;CARBON DIOXIDE&lt;/a&gt;, REFRIGERATED LIQUID is a colorless liquid. Relatively heavier than air and can asphyxiate by the displacement of air. Under prolonged exposure to heat or fire the container may rupture violently and rocket. Used as a refrigerant and in making carbonated beverages. Used to freeze food, to control chemical reactions and as a fire extinguishing agent.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>3</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <Description>Physical Description</Description>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/CARBON%20DIOXIDE&quot;&gt;CARBON DIOXIDE&lt;/a&gt;, SOLID is an odorless, white solid. Can cause damaging frostbite. Noncombustible and nontoxic. Liquefies at -109Â°F. Can asphyxiate by displacement of air. Used as a refrigerant.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>4</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <Description>Ontology Summary</Description>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a one-&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; compound with formula CO2 in which the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; is attached to each &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; atom by a double bond. A colourless, odourless gas under normal conditions, it is produced during respiration by all animals, fungi and microorganisms that depend directly or indirectly on living or decaying plants for food. It has a role as a solvent, a vasodilator agent, an anaesthetic, an antagonist, a member of greenhouse gas, a human metabolite, a member of food packaging gas, a food propellant, a refrigerant, a Saccharomyces cerevisiae metabolite, an Escherichia coli metabolite and a mouse metabolite. It is a one-&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; compound, a gas molecular entity and a carbon oxide.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>8</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a colorless, odorless gas vital to life on Earth. This naturally occurring chemical compound is composed of a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; atom covalently double bonded to two &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; atoms. Medical &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20Dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon Dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a liquefied medicinal gas, supplied in cylinders filled to a high pressure. Medical &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20Dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon Dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may be used in different  situations, e.g.  during bodily investigations,  to inflate body cavities during surgery (such as key-hole surgery), iand in solid form (&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt;) for freezing of tissue and removal of warts.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>18</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <Description>FDA Pharmacology Summary</Description>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a Radiographic Contrast Agent. The mechanism of action of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is as a X-Ray Contrast Activity.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>21</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Record Description</Name>
        <Description>Metabolite Description</Description>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a colorless, odorless gas that can be formed by the body and is necessary for the respiration cycle of plants and animals. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is produced during respiration by all animals, fungi and microorganisms that depend on living and decaying plants for food, either directly or indirectly. It is, therefore, a major component of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; cycle. Additionally, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used by plants during photosynthesis to make sugars which may either be consumed again in respiration or used as the raw material to produce polysaccharides such as starch and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-16211032&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cellulose&quot;&gt;cellulose&lt;/a&gt;, proteins and the wide variety of other organic compounds required for plant growth and development. When inhaled at concentrations much higher than usual atmospheric levels, it can produce a sour taste in the mouth and a stinging sensation in the nose and throat. These effects result from the gas dissolving in the mucous membranes and saliva, forming a weak solution of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used by the food industry, the oil industry, and the chemical industry. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used to produce carbonated soft drinks and soda &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. Traditionally, the carbonation in beer and sparkling wine comes about through natural fermentation, but some manufacturers &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-19660&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonate&quot;&gt;carbonate&lt;/a&gt; these drinks artificially.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>

        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20Dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon Dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a colorless, odorless, incombustible gas resulting from the oxidation of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt;.</StringValue>

      <TOCHeading>Molecular Formula</TOCHeading>
      <Description>A chemical formula is a way of expressing information about the proportions of atoms that constitute a particular chemical compound, using a single line of chemical element symbols and numbers. PubChem uses the Hill system whereby the number of carbon atoms in a molecule is indicated first, the number of hydrogen atoms second, and then the number of all other chemical elements in alphabetical order. When the formula contains no carbon, all the elements, including hydrogen, are listed alphabetically. Sources other than PubChem may include a variant of the formula that is more structural or natural to chemists, for example &quot;H2SO4&quot; for sulfuric acid, rather than the Hill version &quot;H2O4S.&quot;</Description>

      <TOCHeading>Synonyms</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Alternative names for this PubChem Compound record.  A compound can have many different names.  For example, acetone (CH3C(=O)CH3) is also known as propanone, propan-2-one, or dimethyl ketone.  The brand name of a product is commonly used to indicate the primary chemical ingredient(s) in the product (e.g., Tylenol, a common pain killer, is often used for acetaminophen, its active ingredient).  Another example of common synonyms is record identifiers used in different data collections, such as Chemical Abstract Service (CAS) registry numbers, FDA UNII (Unique Ingredient Identifiers), and many others.  All these various names and identifiers that designate this compound are organized under the Synonyms section.  &lt;a href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/docs/subcmpd_summary_page_help.html#DataProcessingSynonyms&quot;&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;</Description>

      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>Depositor-Supplied Synonyms</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Chemical names and identifiers provided by individual data contributors and associated to PubChem Substance records. Synonyms of Substances corresponding to a PubChem Compound record are combined.           <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/CARBON%20DIOXIDE&quot;&gt;CARBON DIOXIDE&lt;/a&gt; is a colorless odorless gas at atmospheric temperatures and pressures. Relatively nontoxic and noncombustible. Heavier than air and may asphyxiate by the displacement of air. Soluble in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. Forms &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt;, a mild acid. Under prolonged exposure to heat or fire the container may rupture violently and rocket. Used to freeze food, to control chemical reactions, and as a fire extinguishing agent.</StringValue>
        </Information>

    <Section>
      <TOCHeading>Therapeutic Uses</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Therapeutic Uses information from HSDB</Description>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Therapeutic Uses</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Brunton, L. Chabner, B, Knollman, B. Goodman and Gillman&apos;s The Pharmaceutical Basis of Therapeutics, Twelth Edition, McGraw Hill Medical, New York, NY. 2011, p. 558</Reference>
        <StringValue>CO2 can be used to flood the surgical field during cardiac surgery. Because of its density, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; displaces the air surrounding the open heart so that any gas bubbles trapped in the heart are &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; rather than insoluble &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-947&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/nitrogen&quot;&gt;nitrogen&lt;/a&gt;. Similarly, CO2 is used to de-bubble cardiopulmonary bypass and extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) circuits. It is used to adjust pH during cardiopulmonary bypass procedures when a patient is cooled.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Therapeutic Uses</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Brunton, L. Chabner, B, Knollman, B. Goodman and Gillman&apos;s The Pharmaceutical Basis of Therapeutics, Twelth Edition, McGraw Hill Medical, New York, NY. 2011, p. 557</Reference>
        <StringValue>Hypocarbia results in ... decreased blood pressure and vasoconstriction in skin, intestine, brain, kidney, and heart. These actions are exploited clinically in the use of hyperventilation to diminish intracranial hypertension.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Therapeutic Uses</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Brunton, L. Chabner, B, Knollman, B. Goodman and Gillman&apos;s The Pharmaceutical Basis of Therapeutics, Twelth Edition, McGraw Hill Medical, New York, NY. 2011, p. 558</Reference>
        <StringValue>CO2 is used for insufflation during endoscopic procedures (e.g., laparoscopic surgery) because it is highly soluble and does not support combustion. Inadvertent gas emboli thus are dissolved and eliminated more easily via the respiratory system.</StringValue>
      </Information>

        <StringValue>Medication (Vet): wart destruction</StringValue>

        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Booth, N.H., L.E. McDonald (eds.). Veterinary Pharmacology and Therapeutics. 5th ed. Ames, Iowa: Iowa State University Press, 1982., p. 1061</Reference>
        <StringValue>Medication (Vet): &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is an anesthetic gas and can be used at a chamber concentration of 30-40% to euthanize small laboratory animals, cats, and dogs less than 3 wk age.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Therapeutic Uses</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Booth, N.H., L.E. McDonald (eds.). Veterinary Pharmacology and Therapeutics. 5th ed. Ames, Iowa: Iowa State University Press, 1982., p. 196</Reference>
        <StringValue>Medication (Vet): Solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is preferred for short anesthesia periods in guinea pigs because it produces no excitement during induction and recovery. The gas has been used to perform cardiac punctures and intradermolingual inoculations. It has also been used to a limited extent in chinchillas, rabbits, and mice.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Therapeutic Uses</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Mahnken AH et al; J Vasc Interv Radiol 19 (7): 1055-64 (2008)</Reference>
        <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18589320?dopt=Abstract</URL>
        <StringValue>/Experimental therapy:/ /The purpose of the stydy was/ to test the feasibility of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO(2))-enhanced computed tomographic (CT)-arteriography in an animal model.  Five domestic swine underwent digital subtraction angiography (DSA), conventional CT angiography with iodinated contrast material, and CO(2)-enhanced CT arteriography. For each CO(2)-enhanced DSA image series, 100 mL of pressurized CO(2) was injected at 1.3 bar. CT imaging was performed according to a standardized scan protocol (2 x 32 x 0.6 mm; 120 kV, 210 mAs(eff), 330 msec gantry rotation time). Iodinated contrast material was administered intravenously according to a biphasic injection protocol. For CO(2)-enhanced CT arteriography, CO(2) was administered intraarterially via a catheter placed in the juxtarenal aorta. An injection pressure of 0.65 bar (volume flow rate, 7.5 mL/sec) was applied. Images were assessed visually by two observers on a four-point grading scale. Absolute intraarterial attenuation values were measured.  Image quality was rated to be the best for standard DSA. CO(2)-enhanced DSA was rated slightly superior to CO(2)-enhanced CT arteriography. No examination was considered to be nondiagnostic. The average multislice spiral CT (MSCT) scan duration was 7.9 sec +/- 0.6. The average amount of gas required for CO(2)-enhanced CT arteriography was 104 mL +/- 4, compared with 400 mL for CO(2)-enhanced DSA. Absolute attenuation values were significantly higher with CO(2)-enhanced CT arteriography (aorta, -928 HU +/- 39) than with standard CT angiography (490 HU +/- 40; P &amp;lt; .0001). CONCLUSIONS: CO(2)-enhanced CT arteriography is feasible. In a porcine model, this technique is capable of depicting the aortoperipheral vessels down to the lower limb. These results warrant further studies of the diagnostic value of CO(2)-enhanced MSCT arteriography for the detection of arterial pathologic processes.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Therapeutic Uses</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Erchinger F et al; Scand J Gastroenterol 44 (9): 1055-9 (2009)</Reference>
        <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19670077?dopt=Abstract</URL>
        <StringValue>/Experimental therapy:/ /The objective of the study was/ to investigate whether the use of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO(2)) compared with air insufflation during colonoscopy improves ultrasonography after the procedure.  In a double-blind trial, 30 patients were randomized to insufflation with CO(2) or air. Thirty minutes after colonoscopy abdominal ultrasound was performed. Immediately after ultrasonography, the ultrasound quality of the liver, gallbladder, biliary ducts, pancreas, spleen, kidneys, abdominal vessels, antrum, bowel, urinary bladder and prostate/uterus was evaluated for optimal ultrasound scanning quality, minor reduction of scanning conditions, major reduction of scanning conditions and unacceptable scanning conditions. Ultrasound quality 30 min after colonoscopy was significantly better when using CO(2) insufflation instead of air (p&amp;lt;0.003). Significant improvement in imaging quality was observed for the liver, portal vein, splenic vein, all three divisions of the pancreas, aorta, coeliac trunk, superior mesenteric artery, iliac vessels, left kidney and uterus. Ultrasound investigation can be done after a colonoscopy with CO(2) insufflation, whereas it is not recommended after a colonoscopy with air insufflation. In selected cases, this approach may enable and improve post-colonoscopy ultrasound scanning.</StringValue>
      </Information>
    </Section>

    <Section>
      <TOCHeading>ATC Code</TOCHeading>
      <Description>The Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical (ATC) Classification System is used for the classification of drugs. This pharmaceutical coding system divides drugs into different groups according to the organ or system on which they act and/or their therapeutic and chemical characteristics. Each bottom-level ATC code stands for a pharmaceutically used substance, or a combination of substances, in a single indication (or use). This means that one drug can have more than one code: acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin), for example, has A01AD05 as a drug for local oral treatment, B01AC06 as a platelet inhibitor, and N02BA01 as an analgesic and antipyretic. On the other hand, several different brands share the same code if they have the same active substance and indications. &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.whocc.no/atc/&quot;&gt;Read more..&lt;/a&gt;</Description>
      <Information>

        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is produced by metabolism at approximately the same rate as O2 is consumed. At rest, this value is about 3 mL/kg per minute, but it may increase dramatically with heavy exercise. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; diffuses readily from the cells into the blood, where it is carried partly as &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-769&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/bicarbonate&quot;&gt;bicarbonate&lt;/a&gt; ion (HCO3-), partly in chemical combination with hemoglobin and plasma proteins, and partly in solution at a partial pressure of about 6 kPa (46 mmHg) in mixed venous blood. CO2 is transported to the lung, where it is normally exhaled at the rate it is produced, leaving a partial pressure of about 5.2 kPa (40 mmHg) in the alveoli and in arterial blood.</StringValue>

        <Name>Metabolism/Metabolites</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>USEPA/Office of Pesticide Programs; Reregistration Eligibility Decision Document - Carbon and Carbon Dioxide pp.8-9 EPA-4019 (September 1991). Available from, as of November 23, 2009: http://www.epa.gov/pesticides/reregistration/status.htm</Reference>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is produced by the body&apos;s metabolism and is always present in the body at about 6% concentration. An average adult human will produce more than 500 g of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; daily under resting conditions, and will produce much more when active. Additional &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; has several effects on the body, and responses are immediate. It stimulates breathing, which exhales the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; carried to the lungs from the cells by the bloodstream. An increase in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration stimulates the heart rate, increases the blood pressure, increases &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5816&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/adrenalin&quot;&gt;adrenalin&lt;/a&gt; flow, and relaxes the vascular smooth muscles. In addition, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; reacts with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; in the body to form &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt;, which dissociates to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1038&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen%20ion&quot;&gt;hydrogen ion&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-769&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/bicarbonate&quot;&gt;bicarbonate&lt;/a&gt;. An increase in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in the body increases acidity, and then the kidneys act to restore normal acidity.</StringValue>
      </Information>

To establish that &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; is metabolized during organogenesis the rates of (14)C-&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; production from 3-(14)C-&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; by conceptuses in vitro were measured on days 9-12. The rates of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; production incr with incr gestational age. ... The rate of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; production from &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; by day 10 yolk sac was 10 times greater than that by the embryo proper. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5236&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Fluoroacetate&quot;&gt;Fluoroacetate&lt;/a&gt; produced a time and concn dependent reduction in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; production in day 10 conceptuses. These studies demonstrate that &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; is metabolized by Krebs cycle during organogenesis. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link multiple-CIDs&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamate&quot;&gt;alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamate&lt;/a&gt; inhibits transport of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; from cytosol to mitochondria. Embryos exposed to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link multiple-CIDs&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamate&quot;&gt;alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamate&lt;/a&gt; exhibited neural tube defects (11/12 at 1,000 uM). Thus, alterations of utilization of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; is teratogenic to cultured embryos. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Pyruvate&quot;&gt;Pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; dehydrogenase is inhibited via phosphorylation by E1-kinase. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-25975&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dichloroacetate&quot;&gt;Dichloroacetate&lt;/a&gt; inhibits e1-kinase resulting incr &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; dehydrogenase activity and incr metabolism of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; by Krebs cycle. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-25975&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dichloroacetate&quot;&gt;Dichloroacetate&lt;/a&gt; produced neural tube defects in 0/12 embryos at 100 uM and 6/15 embryos at 500 uM. ... &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Pyruvate&quot;&gt;Pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; is metabolized during organogenesis and that proper regulation of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; is metabolized during organogenesis and that proper regulation of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-107735&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/pyruvate&quot;&gt;pyruvate&lt;/a&gt; transport and metabolism is essential for normal development.</StringValue>
      </Information>

      <TOCHeading>Mechanism of Action</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Mechanism of Action  information related to the record</Description>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>8</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Mechanism of Action</Name>
        <StringValue>Data not found.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Mechanism of Action</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Andras CD et al; Med Hypotheses 74 (2): 325-9 (2010)</Reference>
        <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19765910?dopt=Abstract</URL>
        <StringValue>Supercritical &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; possesses germicide (bactericide and sporicide) effect. Despite of the fact, that this effect is used in industrial sterilization processes, the sterilization mechanism at molecular level is unclear. Our hypotheses can provide a molecular-biological explanation for the phenomenon. We believe that in supercritical state CO(2) reacts competitively with Met-tRNA(&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;), the formation rate and the amount of formyl-methionyl-tRNA (&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;-tRNA(&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;)) will be diminished by irreversible substrate consumption. The &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;-tRNA(&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;) possesses a key role in prokaryotic protein synthesis, being almost exclusively the initiator aminoacyl-tRNA. The formed carbamoyl-methionyl-tRNA (cMet-tRNA(&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;)), probably stable only under pressure and high CO(2) concentration, is stabilized by forming a ternary molecular complex with the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6830&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/GTP&quot;&gt;GTP&lt;/a&gt;-form of the translational initiation factor 2 (&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6830&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/GTP&quot;&gt;GTP&lt;/a&gt;-IF2). This complex is unable to dissociate from preinitiation 70S ribosomal complex because of strong polar binding between the protein C-2 domain and the modified initiator aminoacyl-tRNA. The IF2-&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;-tRNA(&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;)-blocked 70S ribosomal preinitiation complex does not decompose following the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6830&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/GTP&quot;&gt;GTP&lt;/a&gt; hydrolysis, becoming unable to synthesize proteins. The death of the microbial cell is caused by inhibition of the protein synthesis and energetic depletion. Moreover, we propose a possible mechanism for the accumulation of cMet-tRNA(&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6995182&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fMet&quot;&gt;fMet&lt;/a&gt;) in the bacterial cell. Since the translational process is an important target for antibiotics, the proposed mechanism could be a work hypothesis for discovery of new antibiotics. Made by high conservative character of prokaryotic translation initiation, the proposed IF2 pathway deterioration strategy may conduct to obtaining selective (with low mammalian toxicity) antimicrobials and at the same time, with reduced possibility of the drug resistance development.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Mechanism of Action</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18524954?dopt=Abstract</URL>
        <StringValue>... Well fed C. elegans (roundworm) avoid CO2 levels above 0.5%. Animals can respond to both absolute CO2 concentrations and changes in CO2 levels within seconds. Responses to CO2 do not reflect avoidance of acid pH but appear to define a new sensory response. Sensation of CO2 is promoted by the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-24316&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cGMP&quot;&gt;cGMP&lt;/a&gt;-gated ion channel subunits TAX-2 and TAX-4, but other pathways are also important. Robust CO2 avoidance in well fed animals requires inhibition of the DAF-16 forkhead transcription factor by the insulin-like receptor &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-10666340&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/DAF-2&quot;&gt;DAF-2&lt;/a&gt;. Starvation, which activates DAF-16, strongly suppresses CO2 avoidance. Exposure to hypoxia (&amp;lt;1% O2) also suppresses CO2 avoidance via activation of the hypoxia-inducible transcription factor HIF-1. The npr-1 215V allele of the naturally polymorphic neuropeptide receptor npr-1, besides inhibiting avoidance of high ambient O2 in feeding C. elegans, also promotes avoidance of high CO2. C. elegans integrates competing O2 and CO2 sensory inputs so that one response dominates. Food and allelic variation at NPR-1 regulate which response prevails. These results suggest that multiple sensory inputs are coordinated by C. elegans to generate different coherent foraging strategies.[Bretscher AJ et al; Proc Nat Acad Sci USA 105 (23): 8044-9 (2008)]   Full text: &lt;a href=&apos;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=PMC2410288&apos; target=new&gt;PMC2410288&lt;/a&gt;</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Mechanism of Action</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18524955?dopt=Abstract</URL>
        <StringValue>... Adult Caenorhabditis elegans (roundworm) display an acute avoidance response upon exposure to CO2 that is characterized by the cessation of forward movement and the rapid initiation of backward movement. This response is mediated by a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-24316&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cGMP&quot;&gt;cGMP&lt;/a&gt; signaling pathway that includes the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-24316&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cGMP&quot;&gt;cGMP&lt;/a&gt;-gated heteromeric channel TAX-2/TAX-4. CO2 avoidance is modulated by multiple signaling molecules, including the neuropeptide Y receptor NPR-1 and the calcineurin subunits TAX-6 and CNB-1. Nutritional status also modulates CO2 responsiveness via the insulin and TGFbeta signaling pathways. CO2 response is mediated by a neural circuit that includes the BAG neurons, a pair of sensory neurons of previously unknown function. TAX-2/TAX-4 function in the BAG neurons to mediate acute CO2 avoidance. ... C. elegans senses and responds to CO2 using multiple signaling pathways and a neural network that includes the BAG neurons and this response is modulated by the physiological state of the worm.[Hallem EA, Sternberg PW; Proc Nat Acad Sci USA 105 (23): 8038-43 (2008)]   Full text: &lt;a href=&apos;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=PMC2430355&apos; target=new&gt;PMC2430355&lt;/a&gt;</StringValue>
      </Information>

      <TOCHeading>Human Metabolite Information</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Chemical metabolite information from the Human Metabolome Database (HMDB). &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.hmdb.ca/&quot;&gt;Read more..&lt;/a&gt;</Description>

        <TOCHeading>Metabolite Description</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Chemical description of the compound for metabolite studies</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>21</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Description</Name>
          <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a colorless, odorless gas that can be formed by the body and is necessary for the respiration cycle of plants and animals. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is produced during respiration by all animals, fungi and microorganisms that depend on living and decaying plants for food, either directly or indirectly. It is, therefore, a major component of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; cycle. Additionally, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used by plants during photosynthesis to make sugars which may either be consumed again in respiration or used as the raw material to produce polysaccharides such as starch and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-16211032&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cellulose&quot;&gt;cellulose&lt;/a&gt;, proteins and the wide variety of other organic compounds required for plant growth and development. When inhaled at concentrations much higher than usual atmospheric levels, it can produce a sour taste in the mouth and a stinging sensation in the nose and throat. These effects result from the gas dissolving in the mucous membranes and saliva, forming a weak solution of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used by the food industry, the oil industry, and the chemical industry. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used to produce carbonated soft drinks and soda &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. Traditionally, the carbonation in beer and sparkling wine comes about through natural fermentation, but some manufacturers &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-19660&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonate&quot;&gt;carbonate&lt;/a&gt; these drinks artificially.</StringValue>
        </Information>

      <TOCHeading>Methods of Manufacturing</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Methods of Manufacturing</Description>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Methods of Manufacturing</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Topham S et al; Carbon Dioxide. Ullmann&apos;s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 7th ed. (1999-2014). NY, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: May 30, 2014</Reference>
        <StringValue>Much of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; generated in the world is a byproduct of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-783&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen&quot;&gt;hydrogen&lt;/a&gt; production, which make much more &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; than is ever recovered. Other sources are still exploited, but these are generally less efficient, and financially less attractive.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Methods of Manufacturing</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Topham S et al; Carbon Dioxide. Ullmann&apos;s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 7th ed. (1999-2014). NY, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: May 30, 2014</Reference>
        <StringValue>/&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt;: In the production of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt;/ desulfurization of the hydrocarbon feedstock (e.g., natural gas, naphtha) is carried out before catalytic steam reforming of the hydrocarbon to give a gaseous mixture of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-783&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen&quot;&gt;hydrogen&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt;. Air is added and further steam reforming is effected in a gaseous mixture that then also contains &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-947&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/nitrogen&quot;&gt;nitrogen&lt;/a&gt;. Because only &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-783&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen&quot;&gt;hydrogen&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-947&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/nitrogen&quot;&gt;nitrogen&lt;/a&gt; are required to make &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt;, the carbon oxide is removed from the gas stream. Most of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; is catalytically converted to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, and the latter is removed by dissolution under pressure.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Methods of Manufacturing</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Topham S et al; Carbon Dioxide. Ullmann&apos;s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 7th ed. (1999-2014). NY, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: May 30, 2014</Reference>
        <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; from flue gases. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is a component of all flue gases produced by the complete combustion of carbonaceous fuels. Typical concentrations of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in such gases are 10 - 18 vol%. ... The flue gases, after being cooled and cleaned by passing through a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; scrubber, are passed through an alkaline &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-19660&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonate&quot;&gt;carbonate&lt;/a&gt; solution or an amine solution which absorbs &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. Unlike &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; from an &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt; plant, the product obtained from flue gases is generally contaminated with small amounts of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5362487&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sulfur&quot;&gt;sulfur&lt;/a&gt; compounds. Although manufacture of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; by this method was once of a considerable commercial importance, it is now seldom economically viable. It is, however, being revived in the United States for enhanced oil recovery projects, which require vast quantities of CO2.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Methods of Manufacturing</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Topham S et al; Carbon Dioxide. Ullmann&apos;s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 7th ed. (1999-2014). NY, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: May 30, 2014</Reference>
        <StringValue>Large quantities of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are generated by fermentation processes, and up to 80% of this gas may be recoverable. Before being suitable for further use, however, the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; must be freed of the impurities inherent in this method of manufacture, i.e., &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-402&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen%20sulfide&quot;&gt;hydrogen sulfide&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1119&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sulfur%20dioxide&quot;&gt;sulfur dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, and various organic compounds such as aldehydes, acids, and higher alcohols and diols. Two general methods are available to purify fermentation &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. Both use &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; scrubbers to remove the bulk of the entrained material. The impurities are then taken out by passing through either an activated &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/charcoal&quot;&gt;charcoal&lt;/a&gt; bed or solutions of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-516875&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium%20permanganate&quot;&gt;potassium permanganate&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-24502&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium%20dichromate&quot;&gt;potassium dichromate&lt;/a&gt;. The first method relies on adsorption, whereas the second involves chemical reactions. In the second case the gas must be treated further downstream to remove oxidation products formed in the earlier stages as well as any traces of the reagents used in the purification.</StringValue>
      </Information>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Methods of Manufacturing</Name>
        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Topham S et al; Carbon Dioxide. Ullmann&apos;s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 7th ed. (1999-2014). NY, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: May 30, 2014</Reference>
        <StringValue>Natural sources of gases containing very high concentrations of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are present in various parts of the world. Often the gas is so pure that it only requires drying before liquefaction. The main impurities present in this source of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-297&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/methane&quot;&gt;methane&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-402&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen%20sulfide&quot;&gt;hydrogen sulfide&lt;/a&gt;. These sources are becoming more important in areas where enhanced oil recovery is being practiced.</StringValue>
      </Information>

        <Reference>Lewis, R.J. Sr.; Hawley&apos;s Condensed Chemical Dictionary 15th  Edition. John Wiley &amp; Sons, Inc. New York, NY 2007., p. 233</Reference>
        <StringValue>(1) Gas: for industrial use, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is recovered from synthesis gas in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt; production, substitute-natural gas production, cracking of hydrocarbons, and natural springs or wells. For laboratory purposes it is obtained by the action of an acid on a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-19660&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonate&quot;&gt;carbonate&lt;/a&gt;. It is also a by-product of the fermentation of carbohydrates and an end product of combustion and respiration. Air contains 0.033% of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; ...  (2) Liquid: by compressing and cooling the gas to approximately -37 deg C. (3) Solid (&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt;): by expanding the liquid to vapor and snow in presses that compact the product into blocks. The vapor is recycled.</StringValue>

        <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
        <Reference>Topham S et al; Carbon Dioxide. Ullmann&apos;s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 7th ed. (1999-2014). NY, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: May 30, 2014</Reference>
        <StringValue>The necessary degree of purity is dependent on the final use to which the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is put. Because a large proportion is used in the food and drink industries, the major criteria for the quality of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are that it should be free of odor and taste. Thus, all contaminants that could contribute to these two properties (e.g., &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5362487&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sulfur&quot;&gt;sulfur&lt;/a&gt; compounds, oils, and hydrocarbons) should be removed, preferably to less than mg/kg levels. The main impurities present to any significant degree in the final purified product are usually &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-947&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/nitrogen&quot;&gt;nitrogen&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23968&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/argon&quot;&gt;argon&lt;/a&gt; (from air), and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-783&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen&quot;&gt;hydrogen&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; (if the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; came from a process-gas source).</StringValue>

        <StringValue>Ocean acidification poses multiple challenges for coral reefs on molecular to ecological scales, yet previous experimental studies of the impact of projected CO? concentrations have mostly been done in aquarium systems with corals removed from their natural ecosystem and placed under artificial light and seawater conditions. The Coral-Proto Free Ocean &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon&quot;&gt;Carbon&lt;/a&gt; Enrichment System (CP-FOCE) uses a network of sensors to monitor conditions within each flume and maintain experimental pH as an offset from environmental pH using feedback control on the injection of low pH seawater. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-19660&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbonate&quot;&gt;Carbonate&lt;/a&gt; chemistry conditions maintained in the -0.06 and -0.22 pH offset treatments were significantly different than environmental conditions. The results from this short-term experiment suggest that the CP-FOCE is an important new experimental system to study in situ impacts of ocean acidification on coral reef ecosystems.[Kline DI et al; Sci Rep 2: 413 (2012)]   Full text: &lt;a href=&apos;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=PMC3356889&apos; target=new&gt;PMC3356889&lt;/a&gt;</StringValue>

        <TOCHeading>GHS Classification</TOCHeading>
        <Description>GHS (Globally Harmonized System of Classification and Labelling of Chemicals) is a United Nations system to identify hazardous chemicals and to inform users about these hazards. GHS has been adopted by many countries around the world and is now also used as the basis for international and national transport regulations for dangerous goods. The GHS hazard statements, class categories, pictograms, signal words, and the precautionary statements &lt;a href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/ghs/&quot;&gt;can be found here&lt;/a&gt;.</Description>

        <HintSortByLength>true</HintSortByLength>

          <StringValue>When &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; gas is passed over a mixture of powdered &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5359268&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum&quot;&gt;aluminum&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-14803&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium%20peroxide&quot;&gt;sodium peroxide&lt;/a&gt;, the mixture explodes.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Explosive Limits and Potential</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>International Program on Chemical Safety/Commission of the European Communities;   International Chemical Safety Card on Carbon dioxide (October 2006). Available from, as of November 17, 2009: http://www.inchem.org/pages/icsc.html</Reference>
          <StringValue>Containers may burst in the heat of a fire!</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Explosive Limits and Potential</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>National Fire Protection Association;  Fire Protection Guide to Hazardous Materials. 14TH Edition, Quincy, MA 2010, p. 491-184</Reference>
          <StringValue>Solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-16211683&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium-potassium%20alloy&quot;&gt;sodium-potassium alloy&lt;/a&gt; will explode under a slight impact.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Explosive Limits and Potential</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>National Fire Protection Association;  Fire Protection Guide to Hazardous Materials. 14TH Edition, Quincy, MA 2010, p. 491-154</Reference>
          <StringValue>Mixture of solid forms of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium&quot;&gt;potassium&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (as &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt;) explodes when subjected to shock.</StringValue>
        </Information>

      <TOCHeading>First Aid Measures</TOCHeading>
      <Description>First-aid measures includes important symptoms/ effects, acute, delayed; required treatment.</Description>
      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>First Aid</TOCHeading>
        <Description>First Aid information</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>1</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>First Aid</Name>
          <StringValue>Eye: If eye tissue is frozen, seek medical attention immediately; if tissue is not frozen, immediately and thoroughly flush the eyes with large amounts of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; for at least 15 minutes, occasionally lifting the lower and upper eyelids. If irritation, pain, swelling, lacrimation, or photophobia persist, get medical attention as soon as possible.  Skin: If frostbite has occurred, seek medical attention immediately; do NOT rub the affected areas or flush them with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. In order to prevent further tissue damage, do NOT attempt to remove frozen clothing from frostbitten areas. If frostbite has NOT occurred, immediately and thoroughly wash contaminated skin with soap and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;.  Breathing: If a person breathes large amounts of this chemical, move the exposed person to fresh air at once. If breathing has stopped, perform mouth-to-mouth resuscitation. Keep the affected person warm and at rest. Get medical attention as soon as possible. (NIOSH, 2016)</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>

Do not use &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; on material itself.         <TOCHeading>Fire Fighting</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Fire Fighting information</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>1</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Fire Fighting</Name>
          <StringValue>Excerpt from ERG Guide 120 [Gases - Inert (Including Refrigerated Liquids)]:  Use extinguishing agent suitable for type of surrounding fire. Move containers from fire area if you can do it without risk. Damaged cylinders should be handled only by specialists.  FIRE INVOLVING TANKS: Fight fire from maximum distance or use unmanned hose holders or monitor nozzles. Cool containers with flooding quantities of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; until well after fire is out. Do not direct &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; at source of leak or safety devices; icing may occur. Withdraw immediately in case of rising sound from venting safety devices or discoloration of tank. ALWAYS stay away from tanks engulfed in fire. (ERG, 2016)</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>

          <StringValue>/&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;/ is not effective for use on fires involving chemicals that have their own &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; supply (i.e., &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-44263835&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cellulose%20nitrate&quot;&gt;cellulose nitrate&lt;/a&gt;); or on fires involving reactive metals (such as, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium&quot;&gt;potassium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5360545&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium&quot;&gt;sodium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462224&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/magnesium&quot;&gt;magnesium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5359268&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum&quot;&gt;aluminum&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23963&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/titanium&quot;&gt;titanium&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23995&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/zirconium&quot;&gt;zirconium&lt;/a&gt;) or their hydrides as these materials decompose &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;.</StringValue>

      <Description>Accidental release measures lists emergency procedures; protective equipment; proper methods of containment and cleanup.</Description>
      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>Isolation and Evacuation</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Information related to isolation and evacuation</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>1</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Isolation and Evacuation</Name>
          <StringValue>Excerpt from ERG Guide 120 [Gases - Inert (Including Refrigerated Liquids)]:  As an immediate precautionary measure, isolate spill or leak area for at least 100 meters (330 feet) in all directions.  LARGE SPILL: Consider initial downwind evacuation for at least 100 meters (330 feet).  FIRE: If tank, rail car or tank truck is involved in a fire, ISOLATE for 800 meters (1/2 mile) in all directions; also, consider initial evacuation for 800 meters (1/2 mile) in all directions. (ERG, 2016)</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>

        <TOCHeading>Cleanup Methods</TOCHeading>

        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Cleanup Methods</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Sigma-Aldrich; Material Safety Data Sheet for Carbon dioxide. Product Number: 295108, Version 3.7 (Revision Date 07/02/2014). Available from, as of February 12, 2015: http://www.sigmaaldrich.com/safety-center.html</Reference>
          <StringValue>Accidental release measures. Personal precautions, protective equipment and emergency procedures: Avoid breathing vapors, mist or gas. Ensure adequate ventilation. Evacuate personnel to safe areas.; Environmental precautions: Do not let product enter drains.; Methods and materials for containment and cleaning up: Clean up promptly by sweeping or vacuum.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Cleanup Methods</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Mackison, F. W., R. S. Stricoff, and L. J. Partridge, Jr. (eds.). NIOSH/OSHA - Occupational Health Guidelines for Chemical Hazards. DHHS(NIOSH) Publication No. 81-123 (3 VOLS). Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, Jan. 1981.</Reference>
          <StringValue>1) Ventilate area of leak to disperse gas. 2) Stop flow of gas. If source of leak is cylinder &amp; leak cannot be stopped in place, remove...to safe place in open air, &amp; repair leak or allow cylinder to empty.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Cleanup Methods</Name>

          <StringValue>The gas is heavier than air and may accumulate in low ceiling spaces causing deficiency of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt;.           <StringValue>/&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;/ leaks can be detected by painting suspected areas with soap &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; solution, or by holding a squeeze bottle containing aqueous &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonia&quot;&gt;ammonia&lt;/a&gt; in the area (leaks will be indicated by formation of a white &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-517111&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ammonium%20carbonate&quot;&gt;ammonium carbonate&lt;/a&gt; cloud).</StringValue>

        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Other Preventative Measures</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Sterling EM et al; Brown O, Hendrich HW, eds; Human Factors in Organizational Design and Management II p. 453-64 (1986)</Reference>
          <StringValue>A three phased technique for diagnosing air quality and related ventilation problems was described. Phase 1 consisted of a general overview of the performance of existing mechanical systems, including site inspections. A questionnaire was distributed to all building occupants in order to document the following: environmental problems, symptoms reported in the building, and in order to locate complaint areas for detailed monitoring. The second phase involved measuring &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; concentrations. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; was used as an indicator of contaminant build up generated indoors from occupants and equipment, and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; as an indicator of combustion byproducts infiltrating from the outside, especially from parking garages. The third phase included measuring air exchange rates with tracer gas to determine total ventilation rates within the building and pattern of air movement through the building. As an example of applying the technique, results obtained in a four story, 10 year old sealed, mechanically ventilated, air conditioned office building were given. A four story office building that was 50 years old served as the comparison building. It was equipped with operable windows for ventilation and radiators for heat. Occupants of the study building reported a much higher prevalence of symptoms such as eye, nose, and throat irritation than occupants of the comparison building. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; levels were significantly higher in the study than in the comparison building. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;Carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; concentrations were comparable in both buildings, but higher than those found in similar buildings. Supply of outside air to the first floor of the study building was adequate; however, ventilation system tests and reviewing building plans showed that other densely populated parts of the study building were poorly supplied with outside air due to problems with ventilation design and efficiency.</StringValue>
        </Information>

      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>Nonfire Spill Response</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Information for Nonfire Spill Response</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>1</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Nonfire Spill Response</Name>
          <StringValue>Excerpt from ERG Guide 120 [Gases - Inert (Including Refrigerated Liquids)]:  Do not touch or walk through spilled material. Stop leak if you can do it without risk. Use &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; spray to reduce vapors or divert vapor cloud drift. Avoid allowing &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; runoff to contact spilled material. Do not direct &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; at spill or source of leak. If possible, turn leaking containers so that gas escapes rather than liquid. Prevent entry into waterways, sewers, basements or confined areas. Allow substance to evaporate. Ventilate the area. CAUTION: When in contact with refrigerated/cryogenic liquids, many materials become brittle and are likely to break without warning. (ERG, 2016)</StringValue>
        </Information>

          <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dry%20ice&quot;&gt;Dry ice&lt;/a&gt; should not be kept in container that is not designed to withstand pressure. Containers of other substances stored over &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt; for extended periods generally absorb &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; unless they have been carefully sealed. When such containers are removed from storage and allowed to come rapidly to room temperature, the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may develop sufficient pressure to burst the container with explosive violence. On removal of such containers from storage, the stopper should be loosened or the container itself should be wrapped in towels and kept behind a shield.</StringValue>
        </Information>

        <TOCHeading>Threshold Limit Values</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Threshold Limit Values (TLV)</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>

          <StringValue>Skin: Wear appropriate personal protective clothing to prevent skin from becoming frozen from contact with the liquid or from contact with vessels containing the liquid.  Eyes: Wear appropriate eye protection to prevent eye contact with the liquid that could result in burns or tissue damage from frostbite.  Wash skin: No recommendation is made specifying the need for washing the substance from the skin (either immediately or at the end of the work shift).  Remove: No recommendation is made specifying the need for removing clothing that becomes wet or contaminated.  Change: No recommendation is made specifying the need for the worker to change clothing after the work shift.  Provide: Quick drench facilities and/or eyewash fountains should be provided within the immediate work area for emergency use where there is any possibility of exposure to liquids that are extremely cold or rapidly evaporating.
