      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>Reactivity Profile</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Generic reactivity information from CAMEO.</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>1</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Reactivity Profile</Name>
          <StringValue>Dusts of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462224&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/magnesium&quot;&gt;magnesium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-3028194&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/lithium&quot;&gt;lithium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium&quot;&gt;potassium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5360545&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium&quot;&gt;sodium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23995&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/zirconium&quot;&gt;zirconium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23963&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/titanium&quot;&gt;titanium&lt;/a&gt;, and some magnesium-aluminum alloys, and heated &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5359268&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum&quot;&gt;aluminum&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23976&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/chromium&quot;&gt;chromium&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462224&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/magnesium&quot;&gt;magnesium&lt;/a&gt; when suspended in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are ignitable and explosive. This is especially true in the presence of strong oxidizers, such as peroxides. The presence of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in solutions of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-14488&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum%20hydride&quot;&gt;aluminum hydride&lt;/a&gt; in ether can cause violent decomposition on warming the residue, [J. Amer. Chem. Soc., 1948, 70, 877]. Dangers arising from the use of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in the fire prevention and extinguishing systems of confined volumes of air and flammable vapors are examined. The hazard associated with its use centers around the fact that large electrostatic discharges may be created that initiate explosion, [Quart. Saf. Summ., 1973, 44(1740, 10]. Contact of very cold liquid/solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; may result in vigorous or violent boiling of the product and extremely rapid vaporization due to the large temperature differences involved. If the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; is hot, there is the possibility that a liquid &quot;superheat&quot; explosion may occur. Pressures may build to dangerous levels if liquid gas contacts &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; in a closed container. Forms weak &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt; in nonhazardous reaction with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>2</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Reactivity Profile</Name>
          <StringValue>Dusts of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462224&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/magnesium&quot;&gt;magnesium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-3028194&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/lithium&quot;&gt;lithium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium&quot;&gt;potassium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5360545&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium&quot;&gt;sodium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23995&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/zirconium&quot;&gt;zirconium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23963&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/titanium&quot;&gt;titanium&lt;/a&gt;, and some magnesium-aluminum alloys, and heated &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5359268&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum&quot;&gt;aluminum&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23976&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/chromium&quot;&gt;chromium&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462224&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/magnesium&quot;&gt;magnesium&lt;/a&gt; when suspended in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are ignitable and explosive. This is especially true in the presence of strong oxidizers, such as peroxides. The presence of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in solutions of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-14488&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum%20hydride&quot;&gt;aluminum hydride&lt;/a&gt; in ether can cause violent decomposition on warming the residue, [J. Amer. Chem. Soc., 1948, 70, 877]. Dangers arising from the use of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in the fire prevention and extinguishing systems of confined volumes of air and flammable vapors are examined. The hazard associated with its use centers around the fact that large electrostatic discharges may be created that initiate explosion, [Quart. Saf. Summ., 1973, 44(1740, 10]. Contact with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; of very cold liquid/solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may result in vigorous or violent boiling of the product and extremely rapid vaporization due to the large temperature differences involved. If the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; is hot, there is the possibility that a liquid &quot;superheat&quot; explosion may occur. Pressures may build to dangerous levels if liquid gas contacts &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; in a closed container. With &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; forms weak &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt; in nonhazardous reaction.</StringValue>
        </Information>

          <StringValue>Cotton wool sprinkled with /&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-14803&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium%20peroxide&quot;&gt;sodium peroxide&lt;/a&gt;/ (used in guard tubes) will ignite a few seconds after exposure to moist &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. Exothermic interaction of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-14803&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium%20peroxide&quot;&gt;sodium peroxide&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; heats the cotton which then ignites in the liberated &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt;.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Reactivities and Incompatibilities</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Mackison, F. W., R. S. Stricoff, and L. J. Partridge, Jr. (eds.). NIOSH/OSHA - Occupational Health Guidelines for Chemical Hazards. DHHS(NIOSH) Publication No. 81-123 (3 VOLS). Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, Jan. 1981., p. 2</Reference>
          <StringValue>Liquid or solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; will attack some forms of plastics, rubber, and coatings.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>37</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Reactivities and Incompatibilities</Name>
          <StringValue>Dusts of various metals, such as &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462224&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/magnesium&quot;&gt;magnesium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23995&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/zirconium&quot;&gt;zirconium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23963&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/titanium&quot;&gt;titanium&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5359268&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/aluminum&quot;&gt;aluminum&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23976&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/chromium&quot;&gt;chromium&lt;/a&gt; &amp; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-23930&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/manganese&quot;&gt;manganese&lt;/a&gt; are ignitable and explosive when suspended in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;.           <StringValue>/GUIDE 120 GASES - INERT (Including Refrigerated Liquids)/ Public Safety: CALL Emergency Response Telephone Number on Shipping Paper first. If Shipping Paper not available or no answer, refer to appropriate telephone number listed on the inside back cover. As an immediate precautionary measure, isolate spill or leak area for at least 100 meters (330 feet) in all directions. Keep unauthorized personnel away. Stay upwind. Many gases are heavier than air and will spread along ground and collect in low or confined areas (sewers, basements, tanks). Keep out of low areas. Ventilate closed spaces before entering. /&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, compressed; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, solid; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dry%20ice&quot;&gt;Dry ice&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, refrigerated liquid/</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/GUIDE 120 GASES - INERT (Including Refrigerated Liquids)/ Evacuation: Large Spill: Consider initial downwind evacuation for at least 100 meters (330 feet).           <StringValue>/GUIDE 120 GASES - INERT (Including Refrigerated Liquids)/ Fire: Use extinguishing agent suitable for type of surrounding fire. Move containers from fire area if you can do it without risk. Damaged cylinders should be handled only by specialists. Fire involving Tanks: Fight fire from maximum distance or use unmanned hose holders or monitor nozzles. Cool containers with flooding quantities of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; until well after fire is out. Do not direct &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; at source of leak or safety devices; icing may occur. Withdraw immediately in case of rising sound from venting safety devices or discoloration of tank. ALWAYS stay away from tanks engulfed in fire. /&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, compressed; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, solid; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dry%20ice&quot;&gt;Dry ice&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, refrigerated liquid/</StringValue>

          <Name>DOT Emergency Guidelines</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>U.S. Department of Transportation. 2012 Emergency Response Guidebook. Washington, D.C. 2012</Reference>
          <StringValue>/GUIDE 120 GASES - INERT (Including Refrigerated Liquids)/ Spill or Leak: Do not touch or walk through spilled material. Stop leak if you can do it without risk. Use &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; spray to reduce vapors or divert vapor cloud drift. Avoid allowing &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; runoff to contact spilled material. Do not direct &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; at spill or source of leak. If possible, turn leaking containers so that gas escapes rather than liquid. Prevent entry into waterways, sewers, basements or confined areas. Allow substance to evaporate. Ventilate the area. CAUTION: When in contact with refrigerated/cryogenic liquids, many materials become brittle and are likely to break without warning. /&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, compressed; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, solid; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dry%20ice&quot;&gt;Dry ice&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, refrigerated liquid/</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/GUIDE 120 GASES - INERT (Including Refrigerated Liquids)/ First Aid: Move victim to fresh air. Call 911 or emergency medical service. Give artificial respiration if victim is not breathing. Administer &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; if breathing is difficult. Clothing frozen to the skin should be thawed before being removed. In case of contact with liquefied gas, thaw frosted parts with lukewarm &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. Keep victim warm and quiet. Ensure that medical personnel are aware of the material(s) involved and take precautions to protect themselves. /&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, compressed; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, solid; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dry%20ice&quot;&gt;Dry ice&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, refrigerated liquid/</StringValue>

        <TOCHeading>FIFRA Requirements</TOCHeading>
        <Description>The Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act (FIFRA) allows for federal control of pesticide distribution, sale and use.</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>FIFRA Requirements</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>40 CFR 180.910 (USEPA); U.S. National Archives and Records Administration&apos;s Electronic Code of Federal Regulations. Available from, as of February 4, 2015: http://www.ecfr.gov</Reference>
          <StringValue>Residues of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are exempted from the requirement of a tolerance when used in accordance with good agricultural practice as inert (or occasionally active) ingredients in pesticide formulations applied to growing crops or to raw agricultural commodities after harvest. Use: propellant. Limit: none.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>FIFRA Requirements</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>40 CFR 180.930 (USEPA); U.S. National Archives and Records Administration&apos;s Electronic Code of Federal Regulations. Available from, as of February 4, 2015: http://www.ecfr.gov</Reference>
          <StringValue>Residues of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are exempted from the requirement of a tolerance when used in accordance with good agricultural practice as inert (or occasionally active) ingredients in pesticide formulations applied to animals. Use: propellant. Limit: none.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>

          <StringValue>As the federal pesticide law FIFRA directs, EPA is conducting a comprehensive review of  older pesticides to consider their health and environmental effects and make decisions about  their continued use. Under this pesticide reregistration program, EPA examines newer health  and safety data for pesticide active ingredients initially registered before November 1,  1984, and determines whether the use of the pesticide does not pose unreasonable risk in  accordance to newer safety standards, such as those described in the Food Quality Protection  Act of 1996. Pesticides for which EPA had not issued Registration Standards prior to the  effective date of FIFRA &apos;88 were divided into three lists based upon their potential for  human exposure and other factors, with List B containing pesticides of greater concern than  those on List C, and with List C containing pesticides of greater concern than those on List  D. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is found on List D. Case No: 4019; Pesticide type: insecticide, rodenticide; Case Status: RED Approved 09/19; OPP has made a decision that some/all uses of the pesticide are eligible for reregistration, as reflected in a Reregistration Eligibility Decision (RED) document.; Active ingredient (AI): &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;; AI Status: OPP has completed a Reregistration Eligibility Decision (RED) document for the case/AI.</StringValue>

        <TOCHeading>Interactions</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Interactions</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Interactions</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21350502?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>Reactive oxygen species (ROS) are harmful because they can oxidize biological macromolecules. We show here that atmospheric CO(2) (concentration range studied: 40-1,000 ppm.) increases death rates due to H(2)O(2) stress in Escherichia coli in a dose-specific manner. This effect is correlated with an increase in H(2)O(2)-induced mutagenesis and, as shown by &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-119315&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/8-oxo-guanine&quot;&gt;8-oxo-guanine&lt;/a&gt; determinations in cells, DNA base oxidation rates. Moreover, the survival of mutants that are sensitive to aerobic conditions (Hpx(-) dps and recA fur), presumably because of their inability to tolerate ROS, seems to depend on CO(2) concentration. Thus, CO(2) exacerbates ROS toxicity by increasing oxidative cellular lesions.[Ezraty B et al; EMBO Rep 12 (4): 321-6 (2011)]   Full text: &lt;a href=&apos;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=PMC3077260&apos; target=new&gt;PMC3077260&lt;/a&gt;</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Interactions</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Osol, A., and R. Pratt. (eds.). The United States Dispensatory. 27th ed. Philadelphia: J.B. Lippincott, 1973., p. 232</Reference>
          <StringValue>The responsiveness of respiratory center to stimulation by CO2 ... is depressed by anoxia and various drugs such as ether, alcohol, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6212&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/chloroform&quot;&gt;chloroform&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5288826&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/morphine&quot;&gt;morphine&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-2294&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/barbital&quot;&gt;barbital&lt;/a&gt;, etc.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Interactions</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Wood CD; Undersea Biomed Res 9 (1): 15-20 (1982)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6806959?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>The role of CO2 in hyperbaric &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; toxicity was investigated by administering &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1986&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/acetazolamide&quot;&gt;acetazolamide&lt;/a&gt; ..., tris buffer (tris-hydroxymethyl) aminomethane, and NaHCO3 by ip injection, and by exposure of other groups of animals to an atmosphere of 5% CO2 and 95% O2. All animals were placed in a pressure chamber and maintained at 50 psig in 100% O2 until death. The tris buffer and NaHCO3 buffer significantly extended /the/ time to onset of convulsions and to time of death. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1986&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Acetazolamide&quot;&gt;Acetazolamide&lt;/a&gt; and also 5% CO2 shortened /the/ time of convulsions and significantly shortened survival time. Apparently, increased tissue levels of CO2 play an important role in hyperbaric O2 toxicity. The cause of death in the animals exposed to hyperbaric O2 was pulmonary edema secondary to a systemic hypertension.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Interactions</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Levin BC et al; Toxicology 47 (1-2): 135-64 (1987)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3120355?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>Toxicological interactions between &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; were evaluated in rats. Groups of six male Fischer rats were exposed for 30 minutes to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; and CO2, either individually or in combination, or to the products of combustible materials. Exposure to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; in air caused death within the first minute at concentrations of 4600 to 5000 ppm, which gave carboxyhemoglobin levels greater than 83%. With 2500 ppm &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt;, blood pH decreased from 7.42 to 7.2. The CO2 concentrations tested (1.3 to 14.7%) were neither incapacitating nor lethal. When CO2 was added to sublethal concentrations of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt;, some of the rats died during either the 30 minute exposure period or in the following 24 hours. The rate of formation of carboxyhemoglobin from an exposure to 2500 ppm &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; was 1.5 times greater in the presence of 5.25% CO2. However, this could not explain the increased death rate, since the carboxyhemoglobin equilibrium level (78%) did not change. The combination of 2500 ppm &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; and 5.25% CO2 reduced the blood pH to 6.8. With the combined gases, the total CO2 and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-769&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/bicarbonate&quot;&gt;bicarbonate&lt;/a&gt; values remained low for at least 30 minutes after exposure indicating that a combination of respiratory and metabolic acidosis occurred in animals exposed to both gases. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;Carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt;, CO2 and carboxyhemoglobin levels produced as a result of thermal combustion of 11 natural and synthetic materials at their median lethal concentrations were measured. Only polyphenylsulfone produced sufficient &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; and carboxyhemoglobin levels to suggest &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; as the primary toxicant. For the other materials the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration was too low to account for the deaths observed. It was concluded that in the range of 2500 to 4100 ppm, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; alone has very little probability of causing death, but if it is combined with levels of CO2 above 1.5 % the probability of death is much higher.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Interactions</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Eguchi J et al; Pharmacol Biochem Behav 48 (2): 345-9 (1994)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8090800?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>4-Effects of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-131927&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/MCI-225&quot;&gt;MCI-225&lt;/a&gt;, 4-(2-fluorophenyl)-6-methyl-2-(1-piperazinyl)thieno[2,3-d]pyrimidine monohydrate on experimental amnesia were studied in rats and compared with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1935&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/9-amino-1%2C2%2C3%2C4-tetrahydroacridine&quot;&gt;9-amino-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroacridine&lt;/a&gt; (THA). ... In a passive avoidance task, admin of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-131927&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/MCI-225&quot;&gt;MCI-225&lt;/a&gt; prior to training (1-30 mg/kg po) lessened the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; induced amnesia in a dose dependent manner. THA (0.3-3 mg/kg po) also ameliorated the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; induced amnesia, although slightly in the passive avoidance task. ... &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-131927&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/MCI-225&quot;&gt;MCI-225&lt;/a&gt; lessens impairments in learning and memory without causing serious behavioral abnormalities.</StringValue>

        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Interactions</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Gingras JL et al; Pediatr Pulmonol 18 (1): 13-20 (1994)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7970902?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>To test the hypothesis that respiratory control is altered in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-446220&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cocaine&quot;&gt;cocaine&lt;/a&gt; exposed infants, ... the hypoxic arousal response and ventilatory response to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in 18 term new born infants prenatally exposed to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-446220&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cocaine&quot;&gt;cocaine&lt;/a&gt; and in 10 health, term newborn infants within the first week of life. ... Twelve hr overnight pneumocardiograms were performed on all infants. Results show that 60% (9/15) of the prenatally &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-446220&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cocaine&quot;&gt;cocaine&lt;/a&gt; exposed infants had abnormal hypoxic arousal response and 87% (13/15) had abnormal hypercarbic ventilatory response. Only 6% (1/15) of the prenatally &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-446220&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cocaine&quot;&gt;cocaine&lt;/a&gt; exposed infants demonstrated any abnormality on pneumocardiogram. In contrast, all control infants (10/10) were aroused by the hypoxic challenge and 80% (8/10) had normal ventilatory response to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. No abnormalities were found in the assessment of the overnight pneumocardiogram in the control infants. For the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-446220&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cocaine&quot;&gt;cocaine&lt;/a&gt; exposed infants, test abnormalities were not correlated with concurrent positive urine toxicology for &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-446220&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cocaine&quot;&gt;cocaine&lt;/a&gt;, suggesting that the injury occurs early in development. ...</StringValue>
        </Information>
      </Section>
      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>Toxicity Summary</TOCHeading>
        <Description>Toxicity Summary</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>8</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Toxicity</Name>
          <StringValue>Signs of intoxication have been produced by a 30-minute exposure at 50,000 ppm , and a few minutes exposure at 70,000 to 100,000 ppm produces unconsciousness.</StringValue>
        </Information>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Toxicity Summary</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <StringValue>IDENTIFICATION AND USE: &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) is a colorless gas and liquid, or solid (&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt;): white, snow-like flakes or cubes. It is registered for pesticide use in the U.S. but approved pesticide uses may change periodically and so federal, state and local authorities must be consulted for currently approved uses. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used as a pesticide for insect control in stored grain under modified atmospheres containing approx. 60% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. It is also used as rodenticide (mice and rats). Other uses include refrigeration, carbonated beverages, aerosol propellant, chemical intermediate (carbonates, synthetic fibers, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-7809&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/p-xylene&quot;&gt;p-xylene&lt;/a&gt;, etc.), low-temperature testing, fire extinguishing, inert atmospheres, municipal &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; treatment, medicine, enrichment of air in greenhouses, fracturing and acidizing of oil wells, mining (Cardox method), miscible pressure source, hardening of foundry molds and cores, shielding gas for welding, cloud seeding, moderator in some types of nuclear reactors, immobilization for humane animal killing, special lasers, blowing agent, as demulsifier in tertiary oil recovery, possible source of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-297&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/methane&quot;&gt;methane&lt;/a&gt;, (liquid) carrier for powdered-coal slurry. Supercritical or liquid CO2 used in extraction of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-2519&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/caffeine&quot;&gt;caffeine&lt;/a&gt; and hops aroma; dry cleaning; metal degreasing; cleaning semiconductor chips; paint spraying; polymer modification. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is used in hydraulic fracturing. CO2 is also used as medication during surgical procedures. HUMAN EXPOSURE AND TOXICITY: &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is produced by the body&apos;s metabolism and is always present in the body at about 6% concentration. An average adult human will produce more than 500 g of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; daily under resting conditions, and will produce much more when active. The gas is a weak CNS depressant at 30,000 ppm, giving rise to reduced acuity of hearing and increasing blood pressure and pulse. Exposure at 7%-10% produces unconsciousness within a few minutes. At low concentrations, gaseous &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; appears to have little toxicological effect. At higher concentrations it leads to an increased respiratory rate, tachycardia, cardiac arrhythmias and impaired consciousness. Concentrations &amp;gt;10% may cause convulsions, coma and death. Solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may cause burns following direct contact. If it is warmed rapidly, large amounts of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are generated, which can be dangerous, particularly within confined areas. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; at high concentration in air causes stinging sensation in eyes, nose, and throat. Asphyxiation with CO2 is said to have induced temporary proptosis and mydriasis and caused yellow vision, with transient blindness. Severe damage of CNS and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-638015&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/retinal&quot;&gt;retinal&lt;/a&gt; ganglion cells has been reported. ANIMAL STUDIES: Inhalation of air containing 68% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; for 5 min caused death from asphyxia in pigs. Dogs were given 30% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; for 2 hr, then 40% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, and then abruptly returned to normal air. Eleven dogs died within 10 min with ventricular fibrillation. Four survived with cardiac arrhythmias, and two had no cardiac symptoms. Rats exposed to an atmosphere containing 50% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; died within 6 hr. Rats exposed to 25% died within 36 hr. Deaths were a result of pulmonary injury. Atmospheres as low as 20% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; caused cerebral depression. All rats exposed to 10% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; survived. Guinea pigs exposed to 15% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; for 7 days lost weight at first but later returned to normal weight. They also had higher blood corticosteroids, lower adrenal &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5816&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/epinephrine&quot;&gt;epinephrine&lt;/a&gt;, decreased adrenal &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5997&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cholesterol&quot;&gt;cholesterol&lt;/a&gt;, higher arterial free fatty acids, and decreased lymphocytes in the first 3 days of exposure. No effects were seen in male rhesus monkeys that spent 93 days in an atmosphere with 3% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. Toxicity to fertility (morphological changes of spermatozoa in mice at 1% and testicular changes in rats at 2.5%) and teratogenicity (cardiac and skeletal abnormalities in rats at 6%; skeletal abnormalities in rabbits at 10%) were observed. ECOTOXICITY STUDIES: Harmful to some species of aquatic life in concentrations less than 20 mg/L. Adult and larval insects are rapidly anesthetized by &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. Groups of caged, queenless Apis mellifera (honeybee) workers narcotized with CO(2) on consecutive days early in adult life showed a significantly lower level of ovary activation than did groups of untreated workers. This same experimental treatment, by contrast, is known to accelerate ovary activation and induce egg laying in virgin honey bee queens--an observation that suggests that CO(2) narcosis has contrasting effects in queen versus worker ovary activation. Elevated levels of atmospheric &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, a consequence of anthropogenic global change, can profoundly affect the interactions between crop plants and insect pests and may promote yet another form of global change: the rapid establishment of invasive species.</StringValue>
        </Information>
      </Section>

          <StringValue>Immediate first aid: Ensure that adequate decontamination has been carried out. If patient is not breathing, start artificial respiration, preferably with a demand-valve resuscitator, bag-valve-mask device, or pocket mask, as trained. Perform CPR as necessary. Immediately flush contaminated eyes with gently flowing &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;. Do not induce vomiting. If vomiting occurs, lean patient forward or place on left side (head-down position, if possible) to maintain an open airway and prevent aspiration. Keep patient quiet and maintain normal body temperature. Obtain medical attention. /Simple asphyxiants and related compounds/</StringValue>
        </Information>

          <StringValue>It is recognized that repeated daily exposure at 0.5 to 1.5% inspired &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; at 1 atmosphere is well tolerated by normal individuals. Employment medical examination should be directed to selecting individuals normal in cardiovascular, pulmonary-respiratory, &amp; neurological function. Specific appraisal &amp; standards should incl ... MEDICAL HISTORY- AGE: /Protect from exposure/ individuals over 65, even in evident good health. History of current &amp; past illness: Exclude individuals with recent (5 yr) history of: epilepsy of any form, stroke, fainting, cardiac dysfunction of any form ... chronic resp distress of any form ... glaucoma, mental disease of any form, current endocrine disorder, &amp; gastric or duodenal ulcer. PHYSIOLOGIC AND GENERAL MEDICAL EXAM: General medical exam, blood pressure, electrocardiogram, chest X-ray, pulmonary vital capacity, exercise tolerance step test (masters), red cell count, white cell count, &amp; hemoglobin concn &amp; urinalysis. The results are to be within normal limits &amp; these exams should be repeated periodically; frequency ... detemined ... /by/ physician.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/HUMAN EXPOSURE STUDIES/ ... Twelve healthy submarine volunteers who were exposed at 1% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; for 22 days.           <StringValue>/HUMAN EXPOSURE STUDIES/ Experiments were conducted in ten adult men to determine if rapid eye movement sleep (REMS) reduced the ventilatory response to two steady state respiratory loads compared to slow wave sleep (SWS). A constant addition of 150 (or 200) mL/min pure &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) to the inspirate (7 subjects) and 230 mL of added dead space (5 subjects) were the two respiratory loads. Inspiratory ventilation was measured by pneumotachygraph for at least five continuous min in wakefulness, slow wave sleep and rapid eye movement sleep. The incr in ventilation to both stimuli was equal in slow wave sleep and rapid eye movement sleep with no suggestion of an impaired response during the latter: incr in ventilation during CO2 loading being 49 and 51%, slow wave sleep and rapid eye movement sleep, respectively, and during additional dead space they were 53 and 59%, slow wave sleep and rapid eye movement sleep, respectively. Following the addition of extra dead space, end tidal P(CO2) levels did not rise significantly more during rapid eye movement sleep compared to slow wave sleep (p &amp;gt; 0.5).</StringValue>
        </Information>

          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>

          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2494780?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>/HUMAN EXPOSURE STUDIES/ The cerebrovascular reactivity to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) in the cerebral cortex and the subcortical white matter was measured in 12 healthy adult volunteers (4 young subjects aged 21-24 yr, 4 middle aged subjects aged 34-40 yr, and 4 elderly subjects aged 62-85 yr). Blood flow was computed from the concn history of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-66376&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/xenon-133&quot;&gt;xenon-133&lt;/a&gt; in the volume of interest measured with an ultrapure &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-6326954&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/germanium&quot;&gt;germanium&lt;/a&gt; detector array. End tidal arterial &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; tension ranged from 35.4 to 42.6 mm Hg. The mean +/- SD baseline blood flows in the cerebral cortex were 60 +/- 7, 51 +/- 9, and 33 +/- 4 mL/100 cu cm/min in the young, the middle aged, and the elderly subjects, respectively; the corresponding subcortical white matter baseline blood flows were 21 +/- 1, 22 +/- 3, and 16 +/- 5 mL/100 cu cm/min. Mean +/- SD cerebrovascular reactivities to CO2 in the cerebral cortex were 2.03 +/- 0.58, 1.36 +/- 0.41, and 0.72 +/- 0.19 mL/100 cu cm/min/mm Hg arterial &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; tension for the young, the middle aged, and the elderly subjects, respectively; the corresponding reactivities in the subcortical white matter were 0.69 +/- 0.11, 0.59 +/- 0.17, and 0.36 +/- 0.41 mL/100 cu cm/min/mm Hg arterial &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; tension. Blood flow and cerebrovascular reactivity in the cerebral cortex of the young subjects were significantly higher than those for white matter and significantly higher than those in the elderly subjects (p &amp;lt; 0.001). Age vs blood flow (for the cortex) and age vs cerebrovascular reactivity (for both cortical gray and subcortical white matter) also showed significant linear correlation (p &amp;lt; 0.05). However, the age related changes in white matter blood flow and cerebrovascular reactivity were slow and the differences among the age groups were not statistically significant.</StringValue>

          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2501289?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>/HUMAN EXPOSURE STUDIES/ Eleven female patients (40 to 50 yr) after radical mastectomy were studied while put under a constant depth of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-3226&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/enflurane&quot;&gt;enflurane&lt;/a&gt; anesthesia (1.1 minimum alveolar concn). Tracheal mucosa irritation was induced by injection of distilled &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; at 3 different levels of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; ventilatory drive: resting level of spontaneous breathing (baseline, end-tidal CO2 partial pressure = 50 Torr), relative hypocapnia (end-tidal CO2 partial pressure = 35 Torr, where spontaneous respiratory activity disappeared), and relative hypercapnia (end-tidal CO2 partial pressure was raised to a level of 10 Torr above the baseline). With relative hypercapnia, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; instillation caused only a brief apnea without any changes in blood pressure and heart rate. Although cough reflex, expiration reflex, and spasmodic panting were frequently observed during relative hypocapnia and baseline respiration, the occurrence of these responses was less frequent during relative hypercapnia. No significant changes in blood pressure and heart rate were observed before irritation of the tracheal mucosa at the 3 different levels of CO2 ventilatory drive. However under &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; stimulation, response durations of respiration, blood pressure and heart rate were all significantly longer at relative hypocapnia and were significantly shorter at relative hypercapnia, compared with the baseline values.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/HUMAN EXPOSURE STUDIES/ ... Adding 1% CO2 to air increased the human pulmonary ventilation rate by 37% and 7% on the ground and under a pressure simulating a 5000 m altitude, respectively. Blood flow to the brain increased at 2% but not 1% CO2. CO2 at 0.5 or 1% stimulated hyperventilation to a degree which prevented a decrease in the psychomotor performance at a simulated 5800m, but not a 5000 m altitude.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/HUMAN EXPOSURE STUDIES/ &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; was administered for 15 min to patients with panic disorders (5% CO2, n = 14) and healthy subjects (5% CO2, n = 11; 7.5% CO2, n = 8). Following administration of CO2 and air placebo, changes in behavioral ratings, vital signs, and plasma levels of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-439260&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/norepinephrine&quot;&gt;norepinephrine&lt;/a&gt; metabolite &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link multiple-CIDs&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/3-methoxy-4-hydroxyphenylglycol&quot;&gt;3-methoxy-4-hydroxyphenylglycol&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5754&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cortisol&quot;&gt;cortisol&lt;/a&gt;, growth hormone, and prolactin were measured over three hours. In the healthy subjects, CO2 produced dose-related increases in anxiety, somatic symptoms, vital signs, and plasma &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5754&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/cortisol&quot;&gt;cortisol&lt;/a&gt; levels. In the patients, the frequency of panic attacks (in eight of 14 patients) and the increases in anxiety and somatic symptoms induced by 5% CO2 exceeded those in the healthy subjects and were similar to those induced by 7.5% CO2 in the healthy subjects. The physiologic and biochemical measurements obtained did not elucidate the mechanisms underlying CO2-induced anxiety or the greater anxiogenic effects of CO2 seen in patients with panic disorders.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS/ Effects can be observed in humans at acute doses and during subchronic exposure: from a slight increase of breathing and heart rates at 2-3% (v/v) CO2, panting and tachycardia at 5-6%, to respiratory and heart distress and loss of consciousness at 10%, and finally death if the exposure is not quickly stopped.           <StringValue>/SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS/ The first effect of human inhalation of excessive &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; occurs at concentrations of about 2% (20,000 ppm) when the breathing becomes deeper and the tidal volume is  increased. At 4% the depth of respiration is markedly increased, and at 4.5-5% breathing becomes labored and, for some individuals, distressing. Human inhalation of 8-10% concentrations for periods up to 1 hr showed no evident harmful effects. Other effects of increased &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; levels are increased heart rate, headache, sweating, shortness of breath, dizziness, shaking, convulsions, and unconsciousness. Deaths from accidental exposure to extremely high levels of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; have been reported, but generally analyses of the atmospheres for &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration or the possible presence of other deleterious gases have not been performed.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS/  ... At low concentrations, gaseous &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; appears to have little toxicological effect. At higher concentrations it leads to an increased respiratory rate, tachycardia, cardiac arrhythmias and impaired consciousness. Concentrations &amp;gt;10% may cause convulsions, coma and death. Solid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may cause burns following direct contact. If it is warmed rapidly, large amounts of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; are generated, which can be dangerous, particularly within confined areas. The management of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; poisoning requires the immediate removal of the casualty from the toxic environment, the administration of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; and appropriate supportive care. In severe cases, assisted ventilation may be required. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Dry%20ice&quot;&gt;Dry ice&lt;/a&gt; burns are treated similarly to other cryogenic burns, requiring thawing of the tissue and suitable analgesia. Healing may be delayed and surgical intervention may be required in severe cases.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS/ &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is produced by the body&apos;s metabolism and is always present in the body at about 6% concentration. An average adult human will produce more than 500 g of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; daily under resting conditions, and will produce much more when active. Additional &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; has several effects on the body, and responses are immediate. It stimulates breathing, which exhales the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; carried to the lungs from the cells by the bloodstream. An increase in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration stimulates the heart rate, increases the blood pressure, increases &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5816&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/adrenalin&quot;&gt;adrenalin&lt;/a&gt; flow, and relaxes the vascular smooth muscles. In addition, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; reacts with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; in the body to form &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-767&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbonic%20acid&quot;&gt;carbonic acid&lt;/a&gt;, which dissociates to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1038&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/hydrogen%20ion&quot;&gt;hydrogen ion&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-769&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/bicarbonate&quot;&gt;bicarbonate&lt;/a&gt;. An increase in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in the body increases acidity, and then the kidneys act to restore normal acidity.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ ... An industrial incident was caused by a container of liquid &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; that was unintentionally opened in an enclosed working environment. Twenty-five casualties reached /the authors&apos;/ emergency department. Symptoms included dyspnea, cough, dizziness, chest pain, and headache. ECGs (n=15) revealed ST-segment changes in 2 (13.3%) patients, atrial fibrillation in 2 patients, and non-Q wave myocardial infarction in 1 patient. Chest radiographs (n=22) revealed diffuse or patchy alveolar patterns, consistent with pneumonitis, in 6 (27%) patients and pulmonary edema in 2 (9%) patients. Eleven (44%) patients were admitted to the hospital: 8 were discharged 24 hours later and the others within 8 days. No patient died. Exposure to high concentrations of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; resulted in significant but transient cardiopulmonary morbidity with no mortality when victims were promptly evacuated and given supportive therapy. Cardiac complications were frequently observed and should be actively sought.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ Laparoscopy is a surgical procedure used both for diagnosis and for various treatments. A rare but sometimes fatal complication of laparoscopy is pulmonary embolism with CO2 resulting in pulmonary edema. During laparoscopic gynecological surgery in a 29-year-old woman who had previously undergone lower abdominal surgery, the end-tidal CO2 suddenly increased from 40 mm Hg to 85 mm Hg and then decreased to 13 mm Hg with hemodynamic deterioration. These events are characteristic of a CO2 embolism. When this occurred, CO2 insufflation was immediately stopped and the patient was resuscitated. The patient&apos;s condition gradually improved with aggressive treatment, but the clinical course was complicated by bilateral pulmonary edema. This case of pulmonary edema was soon resolved with supportive management. The formation of a CO2 embolism during laparoscopy must be suspected whenever there is a sudden change in the end-tidal CO2. In addition, the possibility of pulmonary edema should be considered when a CO2 embolism occurs.[Lee Y et al; Yonsei Med J 49 (4): 676-9 (2008)]   Full text: &lt;a href=&apos;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=PMC2615299&apos; target=new&gt;PMC2615299&lt;/a&gt;</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ ... The case of a 50-year-old woman who died of CO2 embolism during elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis /is described/. With the patient under general anesthesia, a 1.5 cm incision was made just below the umbilicus, and a pneumoperitoneum was created by CO2 insufflation with a pneumoperitoneum (modified Veress) needle. Immediately, she experienced a cardiopulmonary arrest and could not be resuscitated. At autopsy, air bubbles were admixed with blood in the epicardial veins and leptomeningeal blood vessels. A triangular 0.1 cm perforation in the left common iliac vein had been created by the pneumoperitoneum needle. A pneumoperitoneum is required for laparoscopy and CO2 is the most commonly used gas. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is highly soluble in blood and fairly innocuous to the peritoneum. Small amounts absorbed into the circulation cause slight increases in arterial and alveolar CO2 and in central venous pressure. When CO2 enters the venous circulation through iatrogenically opened vascular channels, catastrophic and potentially fatal hemodynamic and respiratory compromise may result.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ A 37-year-old parturient underwent emergency cesarean delivery because of severe preeclampsia.           <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ A 44-year-old male, engaged in the transportation of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt;, was found dead on the floor of the freezer of his refrigerator car which was parked in front of the place where he was scheduled to make a delivery. Autopsy was performed to investigate the cause of death. Apart from the signs of acute death, no other significant findings were obtained, either macro or microscopically; &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; poisoning was thus strongly suspected. ... A simulation experiment /was created/ by using the refrigerator car to reproduce the events of the accident. The &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; concentration in the freezer was 21.0% as indicated by &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; sensors, but decreased to 17.1-17.4% when the engine was stopped. This decrease in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; concentration supposedly results from the production of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; by the vaporization of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration in the air could be calculated from the change in the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; concentration in the closed space of the freezer. The concentration was assessed at 17.1-18.6%. An &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; concentration of 17.1-17.4% does not of itself cause serious hypoxia, but a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration of 17.1-18.6% probably causes serious intoxication ... .</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ A 43 year-old woman, with uterine bleeding and right ovary cyst, was scheduled for hysteroscopy-curettage and laparoscopy. Her history was unremarkable. After induction of general anesthesia and tracheal intubation (&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-4943&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/propofol&quot;&gt;propofol&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-3345&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/fentanyl&quot;&gt;fentanyl&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-39765&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/vecuronium&quot;&gt;vecuronium&lt;/a&gt;), anesthesia was maintained with N2O/O2 (60%/40%) and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-3763&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/isoflurane&quot;&gt;isoflurane&lt;/a&gt; 1 vol %. In the recovery room, the patient was restless and experienced blindness for 3 hours. Physical examination and all investigations (EEG, brain CT scan, carotid Doppler and transesophageal echocardiography) were normal. The most probable diagnosis was a CO2 venous embolism associated with an arterial paradoxal embolism responsible for the temporary blindness.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/CASE REPORTS/ In September 2004, in anticipation of a power outage during the aftermath of Hurricane Ivan, a man aged 34 years in Mobile, Alabama, purchased a 100-lb block of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/dry%20ice&quot;&gt;dry ice&lt;/a&gt; from a local &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ice&quot;&gt;ice&lt;/a&gt; house. The windows were closed, and the air conditioner was set to recirculate air inside the cab of the truck. After driving approximately one quarter mile from the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/ice&quot;&gt;ice&lt;/a&gt; house, the man had shortness of breath; his breathing difficulty increased as he drove the next mile. The man telephoned his wife and asked her to call 911. He then pulled his truck into a parking lot, parked, and lost consciousness. His wife drove to the parking lot and located her husband&apos;s truck; immediately after she opened the door to the vehicle, her husband began to awaken. Emergency medical services personnel arrived soon afterward. They determined that the man&apos;s vital signs were normal and he required no further medical evaluation. Although the man complained of a headache for the next 24 hours, he recovered completely.</StringValue>

          <Reference>Abolhassani M et al; Am J Physiol Lung Cell Mol Physiol 296 (4): L657-65 (2009)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19136578?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Acute Exposure/ The aim of this study was to assess whether one of the most common poisons of cellular respiration, i.e., &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, is proinflammatory. CO(2) is naturally present in the atmosphere at the level of 0.038% and involved in numerous cellular biochemical reactions. We analyzed in vitro the inflammation response induced by exposure to CO(2) for 48 hr (0-20% with a constant O(2) concentration of 21%). In vivo mice were submitted to increasing concentrations of CO(2) (0, 5, 10, and 15% with a constant O(2) concentration of 21%) for 1 hr. The exposure to concentrations above 5% of CO(2) resulted in the increased transcription (RNase protection assay) and secretion (ELISA) of proinflammatory cytokines [macrophage inflammatory protein-1alpha (MIP-1alpha), MIP-1beta, MIP-2, IL-8, IL-6, monocyte chemoattractant protein-1, and regulated upon activation, normal T cell expressed, and, presumably, secreted (RANTES)] by epithelial cell lines HT-29 or A549 and primary pulmonary cells retrieved from the exposed mice. Lung inflammation was also demonstrated in vivo by mucin 5AC-enhanced production and airway hyperreactivity induction. This response was mostly mediated by the nuclear translocation of p65 NF-kappaB, itself a consequence of protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A) activation. Short inhibiting RNAs (siRNAs) targeted toward PP2Ac reversed the effect of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, i.e., disrupted the NF-kappaB activation and the proinflammatory cytokine secretion. In conclusion, this study strongly suggests that exposure to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may be more toxic than previously thought ...</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Acute Exposure/ Subterranean storage of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) has been proposed to diminish atmospheric increases of this greenhouse gas. To contribute to risk assessment of accidental release associated with handling, transport and storage, rats were exposed to high concentrations (targets 40, 43 and 50 volume %) of CO2. The &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; concentrations dropped as a result, but were not supplemented. For each concentration, pairs of animals were exposed for different exposure durations to derive an exposure concentration-duration relation in which mortality is described as a function of C(n)x(t) (probit relation). A very high &quot;n&quot; value for the probit function could be derived from the data obtained at 40% and 43% CO2, which indicates that for exposure durations longer than 30 min the LC50 decreases hardly with increasing exposure duration. Below 30 min the LC50 seemed to increase with decreasing exposure durations. The variability in the data of 43% and 50% CO2, however, did not allow to derive a meaningful value of &quot;n&quot;.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Acute Exposure/ The purpose of this study was to determine the length of CO(2) exposure required to euthanize neonatal rats (0 to 10 d old). Multiple groups of rats were exposed to 100% CO(2) for 5 to 60 min. After CO(2) exposure, rats were placed in room air for 20 min to allow for possible recovery. No difference was found in comparing 1 inbred strain and 1 outbred stock of rats. Time to death varied inversely with the age of the animals, requiring as long as 35 min on the day of birth. The time to death decreased steadily with increasing age, with 100% of the rats euthanized after 5 min of CO(2) exposure at 10 day of age. The time required for 100% mortality decreased by 3 min for every 1 day increase in age between days 0 and 10.[Pritchett-Corning KR; J Am Assoc Lab Anim Sci 48 (1): 23-7 (2009)]   Full text: &lt;a href=&apos;https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=PMC2694698&apos; target=new&gt;PMC2694698&lt;/a&gt;</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Acute Exposure/... Anesthetized pigs were ventilated with room air at a fixed minute ventilation. After 1 hr of baseline, they were intravenously infused with CO2 at the rate of 0.3, 0.75, or 1.2 mL kg/min for 2 hr (n = 5 for each group), followed by 1 hr of recovery. All animals experienced pulmonary hypertension, depressed stroke volume, hypoxemia, hypercarbia, and acidemia during intravenous CO2 infusion. They had systemic hypertension at the low rate and hypotension at the highest rate of infusion. End-tidal CO2 levels briefly decreased, then increased in all cases. In the highest rate group, three of the five animals (60%) died at 50, 65, and 100 min of infusion. These three animals had severe hypotension and hypoxemia, with visible coronary gas embolism. There was no patent foramen ovale at necropsy in any animals. The low-flow insufflation rate exceeds the fatal rate of continuous intravenous CO2 infusion. End-tidal CO2 levels were increased in venous CO2 embolism, not decreased as seen in venous air embolism. Severe hypoxemia and hypotension are predictors of potentially fatal cases.</StringValue>

          <Reference>Ikeda N et al; Forensic Sci Int 41 (1-2): 93-9 (1989)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2504656?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Acute Exposure/ To investigate the effects of very high concentrations of CO2 upon the course of respiration and circulation, dogs were allowed to breathe high concentrations of CO2 while intrathoracic pressure, blood pressure in the femoral artery, electrocardiogram and electroencephalogram readings were registered. The respiratory movements either increased just after inhalation of high concentrations of CO2 and then ceased in 1 min, or decreased and continued for a while according to the concentrations of CO2. The blood pressure showed an initial depression, then returned to the original level, then fell again rapidly or maintained an appreciable level for a while until circulatory breakdown. In the dogs allowed to breathe the gas mixture of 80% CO2 with 20% O2, the respiratory movement ceased in 1 min, and the terminal respirations were seen with the circulatory breakdown after apnoea of several minutes. These findings showed that the cause of death in breathing high concentrations of CO2 is not hypoxia, but CO2 poisoning.</StringValue>
        </Information>

Erthrocytic and thrombocytic fragments were occasionally found in the alveolar cavities. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-297&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Methane&quot;&gt;Methane&lt;/a&gt; inhalation caused a similar substance accumulation in the lungs.
