          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Subchronic or Prechronic Exposure/ Nasal epitheliums are the first sites of the respiratory tract in contact with the external environment and may therefore be susceptible to damage from exposure to many toxic volatile substances (i.e., volatile organic components, vapors, and gases). In the field of inhalation toxicology, a number of studies have considered the main olfactory epithelium, but few have dealt with the epithelium of the vomeronasal organ (VNO). However, in several species such as in rodents, the VNO (an organ of pheromone detection) plays an important role in social interactions, and alterations of this organ are known to induce adaptative behavioral disturbances. Among volatile toxicants, health effects of inhaled gases have been thoroughly investigated, especially during CO(2) inhalation because of its increasing atmospheric concentration. Therefore, this work was designed to examine the effects of 3% CO(2) inhalation on VNO in two different exposure conditions (5 hr/day and 12 hr/day) in mice. Behavioral sensitivity tests to urine of congener and histological measurements of VNO were conducted before, during (weeks 1-4), and after (weeks 5-8) CO(2) inhalation exposures. Results showed no significant modifications of behavioral responses to urine, but there were significant changes of both cell number and thickness of the VNO epithelium. Moreover, the findings indicated a selectively dose-dependent effect of CO(2), and further research could use other gases in the same manner for comparison.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Subchronic or Prechronic Exposure/ The inhalation toxicity of submarine contaminants is of concern to ensure the health of men and women aboard submarines during operational deployments. Due to a lack of adequate prior studies, potential general, neurobehavioral, reproductive and developmental toxicity was evaluated in male and female rats exposed to mixtures of three critical submarine atmospheric components: &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-281&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20monoxide&quot;&gt;carbon monoxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO) and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2; levels elevated above ambient), and &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-977&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/oxygen&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/a&gt; (O2; levels decreased below ambient). In a 14-day, 23hr/day, whole-body inhalation study of exposure to clean air (0.4ppm CO, 0.1% CO2 and 20.6% O2), low-dose, mid-dose and high-dose gas mixtures (high dose of 88.4ppm CO, 2.5% CO2 and 15.0% O2), no adverse effects on survival, body weight or histopathology were observed. Reproductive, developmental and neurobehavioral performance were evaluated after a 28-day exposure in similar atmospheres. No adverse effects on estrus phase, mating, gestation or parturition were observed. No developmental or functional deficits were observed in either exposed parents or offspring related to motor activity, exploratory behavior or higher-level cognitive functions (learning and memory). Only minimal effects were discovered in parent-offspring emotionality tests. While statistically significant increases in hematological parameters were observed in the offspring of exposed parents compared to controls, these parameters remained within normal clinical ranges for blood cells and components and were not considered adverse. In summary, subacute exposures to elevated concentrations of the submarine atmosphere gases did not affect the ability of rats to reproduce and did not appear to have any significant adverse health effects.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Subchronic or Prechronic Exposure/ The effect of chronic hypercapnia on neonatal mouse lung /were investigated/ to identify genes that could potentially contribute to hypercapnia-mediated lung protection. Newborn mouse litters were exposed to 8% CO(2), 12% CO(2), or room air for 2 wk. Lungs were excised and analyzed for morphometric alterations.           <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Subchronic or Prechronic Exposure/ ... Neonatal and adult CD-1 mice were exposed to either 8% or 12% CO(2) for 2 wk. We used Western blot analysis of membrane protein fractions from heart, kidney, and various brain regions to study the response of specific acid-base transporters to CO(2). Chronic CO(2) increased the expression of the &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-86590530&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium%20hydrogen&quot;&gt;sodium hydrogen&lt;/a&gt; exchanger 1 (NHE1) and electroneutral &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-516892&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sodium%20bicarbonate&quot;&gt;sodium bicarbonate&lt;/a&gt; cotransporter (NBCn1) in the cerebral cortex, heart, and kidney of neonatal but not adult mice. CO(2) increased the expression of electrogenic NBC (NBCe1) in the neonatal but not the adult mouse heart and kidney. Hypercapnia decreased the expression of anion exchanger 3 (AE3) in both the neonatal and adult brain but increased AE3 expression in the neonatal heart. We conclude that: 1) chronic hypercapnia increases the expression of the acid extruders NHE1, NBCe1 and NBCn1 and decreases the expression of the acid loader AE3, possibly improving the capacity of the cell to maintain pH(i) in the face of acidosis; and 2) the heterogeneous response of tissues to hypercapnia depends on the level of CO(2) and development.</StringValue>

          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19406222?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Subchronic or Prechronic Exposure/ ...This work was designed to evaluate in mice the possible effects of 3% CO(2) in two exposure periods: a 5 hr/day and a 12 hr/day conditions. Behavioral, histological and immunohistochemical observations were conducted every 2 weeks, i.e before (week 0), during (weeks 2 and 4) and after exposure (weeks 6 and 8). Firstly, behavioral evaluations of odor sensitivity showed differences in relation to the odor tested, ie, no effect with congener urine odor and a reinforcement of 2,4,5-trimethythiazoline (TMT) (predator odor) repulsion. Secondly, histological evaluations showed a similar evolution of the epithelium thickness, i.e. a decrease along the exposure as well as during the post-exposure period and an increase of cell number (whatever the phenotype) although the kinetic appeared different in both experimental conditions. Thirdly, immunohistochemical quantification of olfactory marker protein (OMP)- and proliferating cell nuclear antigen (PCNA)-positive cells revealed that the number of mature olfactory neurons increased at the early beginning of exposure period in both conditions. While a decrease was observed in the following weeks (weeks 4-8) for the 12 hr/day condition, a stable amount of OMP-positive cells was maintained in the 5 hr/day condition. In contrast, the number of PCNA-positive cells followed a similar evolution, ie, a constant decrease along the experiment. These findings indicate that the effects of CO(2) inhalation exposure are selectively dose-dependent.</StringValue>

          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Non-Human Toxicity Excerpts</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Li G et al; J Appl Physiol 101 (6): 1556-64 (2006)</Reference>
          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16888043?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Developmental or Reproductive Toxicity/ Despite the deleterious effects associated with elevated &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) or hypercapnia, it has been hypothesized that CO2 can protect the lung from injury. However, the effects of chronic hypercapnia on the neonatal lung are unknown. Hence, we investigated the effect of chronic hypercapnia on neonatal mouse lung to identify genes that could potentially contribute to hypercapnia-mediated lung protection. Newborn mouse litters were exposed to 8% CO2, 12% CO2, or room air for 2 wk. Lungs were excised and analyzed for morphometric alterations. The alveolar walls of CO2-exposed mice appeared thinner than those of controls. Analyses of gene expression differences by microarrays revealed that genes from a variety of functional categories were differentially expressed following hypercapnia treatment, including those encoding growth factors, chemokines, cytokines, and endopeptidases. In particular and of major interest, the expression level of genes encoding surfactant proteins A and D, as well as &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-312&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/chloride&quot;&gt;chloride&lt;/a&gt; channel &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5460341&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/calcium&quot;&gt;calcium&lt;/a&gt;-activated 3, were significantly increased, but the expression of WNT1-inducible signaling pathway protein 2 was significantly decreased. The significant changes in gene expression occurred mostly at 8% CO2, but only a few at 12% CO2. Our results lead us to conclude that 1) there are a number of gene families that may contribute to hypercapnia-mediated lung protection; 2) the upregulation of surfactant proteins A and D may play a role as anti-inflammatory or antioxidant agents; and 3) the effects of CO2 seem to depend on the level to which the lung is exposed.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Developmental or Reproductive Toxicity/ To determine if anesthetic agents used in laboratory animal euthanasia affected sperm motion parameters, rats (n = 10/group) were euthanized by one of 5 different methods: decapitation alone, or decapitation following either ether, &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-3562&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/halothane&quot;&gt;halothane&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-4737&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/nembutal&quot;&gt;nembutal&lt;/a&gt; anesthesia, or &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; asphyxiation. The percentage of motile sperm, their straight line velocity, average path velocity, curvilinear velocity, linear index and linearity were measured ... No significant differences were found among the treatment groups. Thus, none of these 5 methods of euthanasia affect sperm motion as assessed by computer aided sperm analysis.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Neurotoxicity/ Using whole nerve and single unit recording techniques, the responsiveness to &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) dissolved in distilled &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; of free neuromasts (pit organs) innervated by the Ramus buccalis in (carp) Cyprinus carpio, was studied.           <StringValue>/LABORATORY ANIMALS: Neurotoxicity/ &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) gas at two concn (5% CO2 + 95% N2 and 10% CO2 + 90% N2) was flushed into the tympanic bulla of chinchilla ears to study the effects of CO2 on the compound action potential, endocochlear potential, and the pH of the inner ear fluids and the organ of Corti. Gas containing CO2 did not affect the compound action potential threshold, except for a slight decr in compound action potential threshold elicited by an 8 kHz tone burst with 10% CO2 flow. The endocochlear potential did not vary with CO2 gas. The CO2 gas mixture reduced the pH in perilymph significantly, by 0.11 + or - 0.05 with 5% CO2 and by 0.17 + or - 0.04 with 10% CO2, in comparison with a 100% N2 gas flush. The CO2 gas slightly but significantly decr the endolymph pH, by 0.05 + or - 0.04 with 5% CO2 and by 0.09 + or - 0.06 with 10% CO2. The removal of perilymph led to a greater acidification of endolymph with CO2 gas. Acidification of the organ of Corti was also noted with the CO2 gas flush. These findings indicate that CO2 in the middle ear influences the acid-base regulation of inner ear fluids and the cochlear function.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/OTHER TOXICITY INFORMATION/ The circulatory effects of CO2 result from the combination of its direct local effects and its centrally mediated effects on the autonomic nervous system. The direct effect of CO2 on the heart diminished contractility, results from pH changes and a decreased myofilament Ca(2+) responsiveness. The direct effect on systemic blood vessels results in vasodilation.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/OTHER TOXICITY INFORMATION/ CO2 is a rapid, potent stimulus to ventilation in direct proportion to the inspired CO2. Inhalation of 10% &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; can produce minute volumes of 75 L/min in normal individuals. CO2 stimulates breathing by acidifying central chemoreceptors and the peripheral carotid bodies. Elevated PCO2 causes bronchodilation, whereas hypocarbia causes constriction of airway smooth muscle; these responses may play a role in matching pulmonary ventilation and perfusion.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/OTHER TOXICITY INFORMATION/ Tobacco smoking is responsible for a vast array of diseases, particularly chronic bronchitis and lung cancer. It is still unclear which constituent(s) of the smoke is responsible for its toxicity. The authors decided to focus on &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;, since its level of concentration in mainstream cigarette smoke is about 200 times higher than in the atmosphere. ... In this study, the authors assessed the inflammatory potential of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; contained in cigarette smoke. Mice were exposed to cigarette smoke containing a high or reduced CO(2) level by filtration through a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462222&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium&quot;&gt;potassium&lt;/a&gt; hydroxyde solution. The inflammatory response was evaluated by histological analysis, protein phosphatase 2 A (PP2A) and nuclear factor (NF)-kappaB activation, and proinflammatory cytokine secretion measurements. The data show that the toxicity of cigarette smoke may be largely due to its high level of CO(2). Pulmonary injuries consequent to tobacco smoke inhalation observed by histology were greatly diminished when CO(2) was removed. Cigarette smoke exposure causes an inflammatory response characterized by PP2A and NF-kappaB activation followed by proinflammatory cytokine secretion. This inflammatory response was reduced when the cigarette smoke was filtered through a &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-14797&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/potassium%20hydroxide&quot;&gt;potassium hydroxide&lt;/a&gt; column, and reestablished when CO(2) was injected downstream from the filtration column. Given that there is an extensive literature linking a chronic inflammatory response to the major smoking-related diseases, these data suggest that &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; may play a key role in the causation of these diseases by tobacco smoking.</StringValue>
        </Information>

          <StringValue>/OTHER TOXICITY INFORMATION/ The toxicity of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; has been established for close to a century. A number of animal experiments have explored both acute and long-term toxicity with respect to the lungs, the cardiovascular system, and the bladder, showing inflammatory and possible carcinogenic effects. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; also induces multiple fetal malformations and probably reduces fertility in animals. As smokers are exposed to a high level of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (13%) that is about 350 times the level in normal air, we propose the hypothesis that &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; plays a major role in the long term toxicity of tobacco smoke.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>/OTHER TOXICITY INFORMATION/ A blind cross-sectional pilot study was performed ... with the aim of histologically investigating whether intradermal and/or subcutaneous injection of medicinal &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; would increase collagen turnover in rats. Compression of collagen bundles in the tissue samples where intradermal injection was used was more intense than in the subcutaneous treatment.           <Reference>(1) Pierantozzi R; Carbon Dioxide. Kirk-Othmer Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology. (1999-2015). New York, NY: John Wiley &amp; Sons. Online Posting Date: 13 Oct 2003 (2)  O&apos;Neil MJ, ed; The Merck Index. 15th ed., Cambridge, UK: Royal Society of Chemistry, p. 315 (2013) http://volcanoes.usgs.gov/activity/methods/gas/index.php (3) USGS; Monitoring Volcanic Gases.           <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is found in the products of combustion of all carbonaceous fuels. It is found in naturally occuring gases, and as a product of animal metabolism. The &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; content in the atmosphere is about 0.03% vol as a result of the normal balance between animal and plant life cycles as affected by &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; solubility in &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt;(1). Analyses of air in the temperate zones of the earth show 0.027 - 0.036% (v/v) of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;(2). &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is one of primary gases released from volcanoes, along with &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-1119&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/sulfur%20dioxide&quot;&gt;sulfur dioxide&lt;/a&gt;(3).</StringValue>

          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Natural Occurring Sources</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>USGS; Volcano Hazards Fact Sheet. Volcanic Gas. Open-File Report 95-85. March 1995. Washington, DC: US Dept Int., US Geol Survey.</Reference>
          <StringValue>Volcanoes emit large quantities of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is heavier than air and collects in low spots, displacing air in these locations. Hundreds of people have died of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; asphyxiation near volcanoes in the past two decades, most of them in Cameroon, Africa, and in Indonesia.</StringValue>
        </Information>

          <StringValue>The extensive sets of global CO2 measurements of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Admin (NOAA) Geophysical Monitoring for Climatic Change (GMCC) division and of the Upper Atmosphere and Space Research Laboratory of Tohoku University are combined with a two-dimensional transport model to derive, in an &quot;inverse&quot; calculation, the latitudinal and seasonal distributions of sources and sinks of CO2 necessary to reproduce the observed concn. ... It is found that the southern oceans are a sink of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; of 0.8 to 1.5 Gt/yr (1 Gt = 1 x 10 +15 g) and that the equatorial areas are a source to the atmosphere of 1.4 to 2.8 Gt. There seems to be significant seasonality in the sources and sinks of CO2, both in the tropics and in the southern oceans. Seasonal net ecosystem production north of 25 deg N is found to be 6.2 to 8.2 Gt of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt;. ... The global average net source of atmospheric CO2 estimated from the Tohoku data is 2.84 Gt C/yr, while for the GMCC data it is 2.98 Gt C/yr.</StringValue>

          <StringValue>SOURCE DOMINATED: &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; is main greenhouse gas released through human activities(1). Measurements of atmospheric &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in the Northern Hemisphere have shown an increase in the average concentrations from 290 ppm before 1900 to 330 ppm in the 1950&apos;s(2). The amount of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in the atmosphere is increasing as increased amounts of fossil fuels are burned. There is some evidence that the rate of release of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; to the atmosphere may be greater than the earth&apos;s ability to assimilate it. US measurements show an increase of 1.36% of atmospheric &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; content in a five-year period, with indications that content may have increased by 25% as of 2003(3). In 2013, the gas  acounted for approximately 83% of all US greenhouse gas emissions. &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; releases to the atmosphere in the United States increased by approximately 7% between 1990 and 2013. This increase corresponds with increased energy use by an expanding economy and populations, an overall growth in emissions from electricity operations, and an increase in miles traveled by motor vehicles(1).</StringValue>

          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Atmospheric Concentrations</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Thoning KW, Tans, PP; J Geophys Res (D) 94 (6): 8549-65 (1989)</Reference>
          <StringValue>The first 12 yr (1974-1985) of continuous atmospheric &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; (CO2) measurements from the NOAA Geophysical Monitoring for Climate Change (GMCC) program at the Mauna Loa Observatory in Hawaii are analyzed. A digital filtering technique using the fast Fourier transform and low-pass filters was used to smooth the selected data and to separate the seasonal cycle from the long-term incr in CO2. The amplitude of the seasonal cycle was found to be incr at a rate of 0.05 + or - 0.02 ppm/yr. The avg growth rate of CO2 was 1.42 + or - .02 ppm/yr, and the fraction of CO2 remaining in the atmosphere from fossil fuel combustion was 59%. A comparison between the Mauna Loa continuous CO2 data and the CO2 flask sample data from the sea level site at Cape Kumukahi, Hawaii, showed that the amplitude of the seasonal cycle at Cape Kumukahi was 23% larger than at Mauna Loa, with the phase of the cycle at Mauna Loa lagging the cycle at Cape Kumukahi by about 1-2 wk.</StringValue>

          <URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17802595?dopt=Abstract</URL>
          <StringValue>The delta13C value of the dissolved inorganic &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; in the surface waters of the Pacific Ocean has decreased by about 0.4 parts per million between 1970 and 1990. This decrease has resulted from the uptake of atmospheric CO2 derived from fossil fuel combustion and deforestation. The net amounts of CO2 taken up by the oceans and released from the biosphere between 1970 and 1990 have been determined from the changes in three measures values: the concentration of atmospheric CO2, the delta13C of atmospheric CO2 and the delta13C value of dissolved inorganic &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; in the ocean. The calculated average net oceanic CO2 uptake is 2.1 gigatons of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-5462310&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon&quot;&gt;carbon&lt;/a&gt; per year. This amount implies that the ocean is the dominant net sink for anthropogenically produced CO2 and that there has been no significant net CO2, released from the biosphere during the last 20 years.</StringValue>

          <Reference>Goyet C et al; Tellus Ser B Chem Phys Meteorol 43 (1): 1-11 (1991)</Reference>
          <StringValue>Using data from different seasons (July 1984 and February-March 1985), we describe the geographical, annual, and seasonal variability of the partial pressure of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; in sea surface waters of the Southwest Indian Ocean. In Subtropical regions, we observed partial pressure of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; values almost 45 mu atm higher in summer than in winter. This variation is produced principally by the seasonal change of sea surface &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-962&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/water&quot;&gt;water&lt;/a&gt; temperature. In contrast, in the Subantarctic region, partial pressure of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; values 25 mu atm lower in summer than in winter in response to the predominant seasonal biological activity were observed. This characteristic phase change of the seasonal oceanic surface partial pressure of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; signal with latitude appears to be a global phenomenon and is mirrored in the northern hemisphere. A comparison with GEOSECS data shows good agreement between our total CO2 profiles and the earlier observations. In the southern region of the Antarctic convergence, both the measured and calculated partial pressure of &lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; values agree with those of the GEOSECS program, and confirm that this region of the ocean is probably a source of CO2 to the atmosphere throughout the year.</StringValue>

        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>20</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>Atmospheric Concentrations</Name>
          <Description>**PEER REVIEWED**</Description>
          <Reference>Frederiksen D; Proceedings of the American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air Conditioning Engineers Conference IAQ 87 Practical Control of Indoor Air Problems p.217-22 (1987)</Reference>
          <StringValue>&lt;a class=&quot;pubchem-internal-link CID-280&quot; href=&quot;https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Carbon%20dioxide&quot;&gt;Carbon dioxide&lt;/a&gt; concentration was measured in five buildings to evaluate the heating, ventilating, and air conditioning systems. In the first building, CO2 levels increased from the ambient of 350 ppm in the morning, to between 800 and 900 ppm in heavily populated areas from mid morning to mid afternoon. The outside makeup air supply rate was 14 cubic feet per minute per employee, which was below the American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air Conditioning Engineers guidelines of 20 cubic feet per minute per employee. In the second building, the CO2 level increased to 1600 ppm during mid afternoon and the employees complained about stuffy air. In the third building the employees complained about respiratory problems, although the 24 hour cycle chart showed CO2 levels between 500 and 600 ppm, indicating an adequate air supply. However, the waterfall wash humidification system was loaded with slime and bacteria, as no bacteriacide had ever been used. In the fourth building spot checks revealed high CO2 levels, which were found to be due to an occupancy level problem. The occupancy on the main floor averaged less than 50 square feet per person which is substantially below the American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air conditioning Engineers recommended 143 square feet per person. Stuffy air complaints in the fifth building prompted CO2 spot checks. The CO2 level in the heating, ventilating, and air conditioning supply was 450 to 550 ppm, while the level was as high as 950 ppm in the building. An investigation revealed tampering with the variable air volume control boxes. It was concluded that CO2 measurement can provide a quick verification of outside air supply rates and air distribution.</StringValue>
        </Information>

    <Section>
      <TOCHeading>Springer Nature References</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Literature references related to scientific contents from Springer Nature journals and books. These references have been ranked automatically by an algorithm which calculates the relevance for each substance in a Springer Nature document. It is based on: 1. the TF-IDF, adapted to chemical structures, 2. location information in the text (e.g. title, abstract, keywords), and 3. the document size.  Springer Nature aims to provide only high qualitative and relevant content but references of lower relevance aren&apos;t withheld as they might contain also very useful information</Description>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>36</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Springer Nature References</Name>

    <Section>
      <TOCHeading>Chemical Co-Occurrences in Literature</TOCHeading>
      <Description>Chemical co-occurrences in literature highlight chemicals that are found mentioned together in scientific articles.  This may suggest an important relationship exists between the two chemicals.  The lists of chemicals are ordered by count of publications with co-occurrences.  The publications are prioritized such that the most relevant mentions appear at the top.  Please note that this content is generated by text-mining algorithms (i.e., it is not human curated).  It is possible that the algorithms get fooled such that a co-occurrence may be happenstance or a casual mention.</Description>
      <Information>
        <ReferenceNumber>41</ReferenceNumber>
        <Name>Chemical Co-Occurrences in Literature</Name>
        <BoolValue>true</BoolValue>
      </Information>
    </Section>

It is possible that the algorithms get fooled such that a co-occurrence may be happenstance or a casual mention.</Description>

      <Section>
        <TOCHeading>WHO ATC Classification System</TOCHeading>
        <Description>The Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical (ATC) Classification System is used for the classification of drugs. This pharmaceutical coding system divides drugs into different groups according to the organ or system on which they act and/or their therapeutic and chemical characteristics. Each bottom-level ATC code stands for a pharmaceutically used substance, or a combination of substances, in a single indication (or use). This means that one drug can have more than one code: acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin), for example, has A01AD05 as a drug for local oral treatment, B01AC06 as a platelet inhibitor, and N02BA01 as an analgesic and antipyretic. On the other hand, several different brands share the same code if they have the same active substance and indications. &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.whocc.no/atc/&quot;&gt;Read more..&lt;/a&gt;</Description>
        <Information>
          <ReferenceNumber>51</ReferenceNumber>
          <Name>HID</Name>
          <URL>https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/classification/#hid=79</URL>
          <NumValue>79</NumValue>
        </Information>
      </Section>
